<HEAD>Denver Minister Threatens To Drop Boy Scouts Over Homosexual Stance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE WHEELAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> minister said Monday that he would drop his church's sponsorship of a Boy Scout troop unless the organization reverses itself and allows a homosexual man to serve on the troop's parents committee. `` I believe the Boy Scout law is a correct one _ to serve God and country,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Ostertag </PERSON>, rector of <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barnabas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>. `` But I do n't think God or my country trashes people. If the Boy Scouts have departed from that, they should let the sponsoring agencies know they have departed from that old law.'' <PERSON> Ostertag </PERSON> said the homosexual man, who has a son in Troop 13, was one of 16 people appointed to the parents committee, which supervises the activities of the 35 scouts in the troop. He said the Boy Scout organization revoked the man's registration after learning that he was an admitted homosexual. <PERSON> Ostertag </PERSON> would not name the father. The Boy Scouts of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has upheld the decision at the district and regional levels. The case now is before the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> of the Boy Scouts, <PERSON> Ostertag </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Barclay </PERSON> <PERSON> Bollas </PERSON>, a spokesman at the organization's national headquarters in <LOCATION> Irving </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said Monday that the <ORGANIZATION> Boy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Scouts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> has a policy barring membership to homosexuals and has invoked that policy before. `` We do not believe homosexuals make appropriate leaders for a youth organization like the Boy Scouts,'' <PERSON> Bollas </PERSON> said. Both the troop committee and the parents of the scouts have voted to support <PERSON> Ostertag </PERSON>'s campaign on behalf of the man. <PERSON> Ostertag </PERSON> said it is not easy finding volunteers who will take scouts on camping trips and oversee their work on merit badges, especially in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION> neighborhood, where many residents are single. `` This is Holy Week, and I feel uncomfortable celebrating Good Friday and then having to turn around to this man and say, ` You're trash, and we do n't want you around,''' the minister said `` I do n't go for that.
