<HEAD>U.S. Agencies Apparently In Conflict Over Rocket Fuel Bound For Iran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Customs officials are trying to block a shipment of a rocket fuel component allegedly headed for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, but a lack of cooperation between federal agencies could help free the chemical soon, it was reported. A shipment large enough to fuel 300 military missiles was seized in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in February 1988 when <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> agents said it was being loaded onto an Iranian freighter, according to Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. But the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued a special export license to the chemical's owner, blocking Customs' court fight to forbid the shipment, the newspaper said. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> issued a temporary injunction requiring the government to release the 1,144 drums of ammonium perchlorate last week. Another hearing is scheduled for today. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Sim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lake </PERSON> ruled the rocket fuel ingredient was not among munitions restricted for shipment to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> by the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and that Customs failed to prove the shipment was bound for <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The 286,000 pounds of the rocket fuel component shipped from <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> in January 1988 by <ORGANIZATION> Grindius </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, was seized the following month as it was being loaded onto an Iranian freighter in the <LOCATION> Dutch </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Rotterdam </LOCATION>. The shipment was being sent during the Iran-Iraq war, when those countries were using surface-to-surface missiles. <PERSON> Grindius </PERSON> contends it never intended to sell the chemical to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The shipping bill of lading shows it was bound for a buyer in <LOCATION> Basel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. Following the seizure, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> issued a special export license covering the shipment. The <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has urged the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to revoke the license. The department has declined to do so and would n't comment on the case pending its court outcome. Customs officials also said the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is not sure whether it will pursue the agency's case because of <PERSON> Lake </PERSON>'s initial ruling. Lake blamed a lack of cooperation and communication between the various governmental agencies for the apparent conflict. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> exports between 1 million and 2 million pounds of ammonium perchlorate every year, mostly to friendly nations. The compound has been in short supply since May when an explosion in <LOCATION> Henderson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>, destroyed a plant operated by <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the primary manufacturer of ammonium perchlorate.
