<FIRST>r w PM-OldandPoor     03-20 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Old and Poor,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Documentary Shows Troubles of Elderly Poor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` That's my problem, I'm a survivor,'' said the old woman. As she said it, she raised her blue eyes so they made contact with the social worker sitting across the table and, coincidentally, with the camera. There was a smile on her face as she talked about how strong she was, how strong she had been all her life, how she had always taken care of herself _ and of her husband before he died. But now, she was alone and sick and poor and beyond finding much to look forward to on <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. The more she talked the sadder she became until she concluded that `` 68 is long enough to live.'' And then she wept. It is but one of several such scenes from a television documentary _ `` On the Other Side of Easy Street'' _ airing this week on Public Broadcasting System stations across the nation. Without exception, the old people put on faces of strength, even humor for the camera. But they are not actors and, also without exception, their eyes reflect despair and, in some cases, a bewildered sense that they thought it was n't supposed to turn out this way. Indeed, that is the central point to the film: that despite the Social Security program that has helped keep an increasing proportion of elderly Americans from the poverty that afflicted their own elders, those who remain poor _ well over 3 million _ do so with little hope. `` The film shatters the stereotype that elderly persons are well off and none are poor,'' said <PERSON> Horace </PERSON> <PERSON> Deets </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retired </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Persons </ORGANIZATION>. `` ... So many people struggle every day to retain some dignity in the face of extreme poverty.'' <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Villers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, which financed the film along with <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION>, said after a preview screening that the problems portrayed in the film `` are not insoluble.'' `` Frankly, it's a question of political will,'' said <PERSON> Pollack </PERSON>, who made the point that _ unlike younger and healthier people _ the elderly have little prospect of working their way out of poverty. While not a pleasant viewing experience, the film drives home the point that even the best laid plans do n't always turn out. And it shows that cutting through government red tape to get available benefits is not the easiest thing to do, especially for a new widow reeling from the death of her husband from a long illness that wiped out what they thought would be a financial cushion. <ORGANIZATION> AARP </ORGANIZATION> issued a study in conjunction with release of the film that showed fewer than half the elderly people eligible for the Supplemental Security Income program, which is supposed to provide a safety net for the poorest of the poor, actually get their benefits. The reasons vary widely from state to state and individual to individual but, in most cases, result from failure of the bureaucracy make the program easily available for those too unsophisticated or too proud to seek it out. For those who do, the maximum benefit is $ 368 per month for an individual and $ 553 per month for a couple.
