<HEAD>Nominee Faced Grilling on Warm Milk, Cigarettes and Derrieres</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In the aftermath of the brutal <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> battle over former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>'s attempt to run the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>, the tenor of a confirmation hearing seems to be getting, as one senator says, a little bizarre. As evidence, here are a few questions put by Sen. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.H. </LOCATION>, to <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> during his confirmation hearing last week to be deputy secretary of state: <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>: Well, let's get to the important questions, Mr. <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>. ... First of all, have you ever drunk anything stronger than warm milk? <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>: Yes, sir. -LRB- Laughter -RRB- <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>: Strike one. I notice you smoke, too. Strike two. ... Have you ever in public or private pinched a woman's behind? <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>: Can I divide that into two questions? -LRB- Laughter -RRB- ... No, sir. The nominee, a man to whom laughter came as easily as diplomatic analysis during the drawn-out hearings, apparently took no offense at <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON>'s questions and went on to discuss with him the tragedy of hunger that is gripping the African nation, <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. The 30-year veteran of government service, who'd accumulated a massive store of goodwill among senators, was swiftly confirmed a day later by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. But all kidding aside, <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>'s two days of confirmation hearings served to point out that much confusion remains about what is required of a nominee for high public office, whether in personal standards of conduct, or in attempting to deal with questions of real or apparent conflict of interest. It was clear that the shadow of Tower's ruined quest for confirmation, which foundered on allegations of alcohol abuse, `` womanizing'' and the nominee's $ 1 million in fees as a consultant for defense contractors, haunted <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>'s nomination, and may well haunt others in the future. Some of the most tense questioning during the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Foreign Relations Committee hearings came from Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, R.-N. He prodded <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> about the more than $ 900,000 in income, bonuses and severance the nominee received during his last of four years with the international consulting firm headed by former Secretary of State <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>. `` You know the big deal that was made about <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> told <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>. `` He was a piker compared to your income.'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, an arch-conservative who had been a vocal critic of <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s policy of pursuing detente, said he was worried about possible influence by the firm's foreign clients. `` There are a lot of people who wonder whether the advice you might give to the president or the secretary of state might be colored by the ongoing interest of firms, foreign firms ... who have been paying you substantial fees,'' <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> told <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>. <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said he had provided analyses of political, economic and societal developments for his clients, many of them multinational corporations, but that he never lobbied the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government on their behalf or engaged in any political activity for them. To return to government and avoid `` even the appearance of a conflict of interest,'' <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said he cut all ties with <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> <PERSON> Associates </PERSON>, sold all his investment stocks, and volunteered to disqualify himself for a year from any dealings with the 15 clients he'd worked for while at <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON>'s firm and been paid more than $ 5,000. This, his attorney <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> argued, went `` far beyond'' what has customarily been required from government appointees, such as cutting all ties with their former business associates and then being recused on a case-by-case basis on the advice of government ethics attorneys. But <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON>'s actions did not satisfy <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, who said he wanted the names of all of the <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> clients made public, whether <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> had worked for them or not. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> argued that since <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> had been paid out of a company pot of funds, and not just by the clients he served, it was necessary for the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel to have such information. <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> said that was difficult for him, since the list was considered confidential by the company. <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>' request proved too much for Sen. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Biden </PERSON>, D-Del., who argued that `` it's bizarre'' to require a nominee to disqualify himself from all dealings with any client that paid part of his income, even though he'd had no business dealings with them He said such a requirement would have disqualified former Secretary of State <PERSON> Cyrus </PERSON> <PERSON> Vance </PERSON>, former deputy secretary of state <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitehead </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON>, many of whom had extensive business contacts with huge investment or law firms. `` I think we're getting a little daffy. ... We'll be assured that the only person who'll we'll ever have as a secretary of state will be someone who has a career that is distinguished by doing nothing,'' <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> argued. <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> sought to defuse the problem by offering to disqualify himself from any possible future dealings with any client of the <PERSON> Kissinger </PERSON> firm from the past two years, even those he did n't work with As well, an `` informal'' arrangement was worked out, <PERSON> Biden </PERSON> said, that did not require the nominee to meet a higher standard than what is required under the law. <PERSON> Eagleburger </PERSON> agreed to disclose the names of the clients to the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> legal adviser, who is obligated to keep them private under an attorney-client relationship, and provide the list to the committee chairman, Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, who agreed to treat it as a classified document.
