<HEAD>1990s Look Good for US Farm Exports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Do n't look for the super-heated exports of the 1970s to return soon, but an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> economist says rising global demand for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural products could bring at least a miniboom in the 1990s. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> says the growing demand is n't expected to match the fast pace of the 1970s when the volume of farm exports rose an average of 9 percent a year. The world's economic growth rate in the 1990s simply is not expected to support that kind of growth. But incomes in other countries are likely to rise faster in the next decade than they have in the 1980s, <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> said. And higher incomes should translate into greater demand for agricultural products. `` The best markets for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will be the developing countries,'' <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> said in an article prepared for the April issue of Farmline magazine. `` More of the world's population will seek higher quality diets,'' he said. `` We will see a continuing gradual change toward higher valued and processed products, such as meats, fruits and vegetables, and dairy products.'' People with rising incomes will want more protein, and that will generate a growing demand for livestock feed, such as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, so the countries can produce more meat, <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> said. Foreign use of feed grains is expected to climb faster than food grains, which include wheat and rice. <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> and his agency colleagues say they ca n't make a flat prediction about the'90s being the start of a golden era because `` the future demand for American farm products could be either stifled or stimulated'' by any number of factors: _ Last year's crop-depleting drought in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> could trigger larger production by some export competitors wanting to cash in on the higher commodity prices _ Developing countries could let domestic food prices rise, thus encouraging farmers to produce more food for their own people In general, that would tend to boost import demand by raising incomes _ and when incomes rise, demand usually outruns a country's ability to produce. _ The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s import needs, particularly for soybean meal and other high-protein feeds, are unknown at this time _ The outcome of current negotiations under <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, and the future of trade barriers and export subsidies <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> said the years 1981-88, when <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> shipments abroad tumbled, showed that exports are critical to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> agriculture, and when they suffer, so do farmers. `` The production from about one of every three acres harvested in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is marketed to consumers in other countries,'' <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> said. `` In recent years, the value of total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agricultural exports averaged more than $ 16,000 a farm.'' <PERSON> Trostle </PERSON> said foreign demand for agricultural products will probably grow more slowly in the 1990s than it did in the 1970s _ but faster than it did in the first half of the 1980s. He cited several forces that help shape this outlook: _ World population growth has slowed from a peak of 2 percent annually in the 1960s to about 1.7 percent now, and the trend is expected to continue Even so, the slower growth will add about 80 million more mouths to feed each year. _ Many countries will have slower income growth than in the 1970s, but the increases in the'80s are projected to be faster than in the early 1980s, particularly in the developing countries _ Surpluses will continue to be more common than shortages in world markets, so most commodities will be priced competitively, often with favorable credit terms _ Debt problems will continue to hold back both income and import demand in debtor countries, but to a lesser degree over time as debt is gradually retired, restructured, forgiven or otherwise resolved
</TEXT>
