<HEAD>Congress Pushing Housing, Homelessness Bills</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is trying to move the issues of affordable housing and homelessness to the forefront of the national agenda, after eight years of cutbacks under the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. More than a quarter of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> last week co-sponsored a bill that seeks to address the housing concerns of everyone from first-time home buyers to the homeless. The bill, called the National Affordable Housing Act, seeks `` to set the framework for a new national housing strategy'' said Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the Banking, Housing and Urban Affairs subcommittee on housing `` It is imperative that we reverse a decade of neglect in housing. ... I sense a growing impatience to raise housing back to the place it deserves in the nation's priorities,'' said <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, the bill's primary sponsor. The act would require states and local governments to submit five-year housing plans to the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> and update the plans annually. It also would create a single institution within <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> with the authority to provide direct assistance to government agencies. It would establish an assistant housing secretary post to administer programs for the elderly, handicapped and homeless. For individuals the bill would seek to reduce the size of down payments and allow first-time home buyers to use funds from individual retirement accounts or 401K retirement plans for the investment, reduce <ORGANIZATION> FHA </ORGANIZATION> mortgage rates while increasing the ceiling of loan amounts in many cases and set limits on the percentage of income paid by tenants receiving rental assistance. Low-income tax credits for developers set to expire next year would be made permanent through provisions set forth in an earlier bill co-sponsored by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION> and Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Danforth </PERSON>, R-Mo. There have been `` no specific commitments'' from the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration but housing secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> likes many of the bill's elements is `` very interested in the measure,'' according to <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, who has met with <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> several times. `` We're going to enact housing legislation this session,'' declared <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>. The subcommittee will begin hearings on the proposal next month. As the <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> bill came out of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gonzalez </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, held the second in a series of all-day hearings on the need for permanent housing for the homeless. Earlier in the month, Sen. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., challenged <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` to show the leadership this issue demands'' and called for a White House conference on homelessness In addition, Sen. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikulski </PERSON>, D-Md., is set to challenge the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration if it intends to replace rental assistance certificates with vouchers as proposed in former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s <PERSON> Mikulski </PERSON> has released a study by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZ