<FIRST>u a PM-Poll-S&amp;Ls Bjt   03-20 0672</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poll-S&amp;Ls, Bjt,0686</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poll Finds Doubt That Feds Can Solve S&amp;L Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans widely expect the federal government to fail in its search for a lasting solution to the savings and loan crisis, a national survey by <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> has found. The poll of 1,108 adults also revealed a considerable lack of confidence in the beleaguered S & amp; L industry: Only half the respondents called thrifts safe and a third of those with <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L deposits feared losing their money. Half those surveyed favored greater government regulation of the industry, and a majority preferred bailing out failing thrifts to closing them. But most opposed having the public bear the brunt of the costs. Federal insurance is insufficient to cover accounts at the estimated 350 savings and loans that are failing, and the government so far has taken over 166 of them while <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> devise a rescue plan. The nation has 2,955 savings and loan associations in all. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has proposed using $ 50 billion in government-backed bonds to help cover the accounts, in addition to $ 40 billion pledged last year to sell or prop up failed thrifts. But in the poll just 27 percent said the government should pay most of the costs of salvaging the industry. Instead, a 42 percent plurality said the S & amp; L industry should bear most of the costs by paying higher insurance premiums on its accounts, a lesser feature of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan. Just 14 percent supported a fee on S & amp; L depositors, an idea the administration considered and dropped. Whatever the eventual plan, only 31 percent believed the government will find a long-term solution to the crisis. Thirty-nine percent expected `` only a temporary solution'' and 19 percent predicted no solution. The rest expressed no opinion. The survey did find support for the government program of giving <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ls financial assistance to attract buyers. Of those who had an opinion, 51 percent favored such bailouts while 29 percent preferred closing down failing thrifts and paying off their depositors. Of the 35 percent of respondents who had S & amp; L accounts, only 9 percent said they were withdrawing money because of the industry's problems But a fifth said they were considering that step and as many said they were holding off on new deposits. S & amp; Ls have sustained record withdrawals lately, but federal analysts have chiefly blamed the higher interest rates that are available elsewhere rather than concern about the industry's financial problems But while the poll found that the S & amp; L crisis had not yet prompted many depositors to reduce their accounts, others said they were staying away. Of those who have not had money in S & amp; Ls during the past year, 18 percent said they were keeping their money out because of the thrifts' woes. The industry problems were widely recognized: Only 53 percent overall regarded S & amp; Ls as a safe place to keep their money, compared with 93 percent who saw banks as safe. Thirty-six percent called S & amp; Ls unsafe and 11 percent were n't sure. A 48 percent plurality blamed the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L crisis on bad management by the thrifts; among other respondents with an opinion, 21 percent blamed general economic problems and 11 percent blamed fraud by <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L managers. Only 10 percent blamed a lack of government regulation. But 53 percent nonetheless favored bolstering goverment regulation, twice the number who said current regulation was `` about right.'' The survey, conducted March 6-15, found relatively little variation in opinion across the demographic spectrum. In the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION>, where thrifts have fared worst, 49 percent rated them safe; in the Northeast, 56 percent called them safe. That gap slightly exceeded the margin of error plus or minus 3 percentage points. The poll was conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Media </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a communications company based in <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, that publishes the Richmond Times-Dispatch, the Richmond News Leader, the <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION> -RRB- <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> Winston-Salem </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> -RRB- Journal, and operates TV stations <ORGANIZATION> WXFL </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tampa </LOCATION>, WCBD in <LOCATION> Charleston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> WJKS </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>.
