<HEAD>AP Photographer Pyle Dies of Heart Ailment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> photographer whose assignments took him from papal travels in <LOCATION> Latin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Super </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bowls </LOCATION> and Olympic Games, has died. He was 45. <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> photo editor, died Saturday after surviving more than a month on an artificial heart-assist device. He suffered a heart attack Feb. 12 and underwent multiple bypass surgery. Doctors determined <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON>'s heart still was too damaged to resume normal pumping and he was connected to devices that helped his heart pump blood. Doctors had hoped <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON> would become a candidate for a heart transplant. <PERSON> Pyle </PERSON>, a 16-year AP veteran, headed <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> photo operations for the news cooperative the past 13 years and frequently handled out-of-state assignments. He covered five trips by popes; the U.S.-Soviet summit in <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>; political conventions; and the shuttle Challenger disaster. His sports assignments included Super Bowls, World Series, the <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Derby </LOCATION> and Olympics at <LOCATION> Calgary </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> was one of the very good people who possessed the rare talent to operate as effectively with newspaper publishers and general managers as with fellow photographers, covering everything from street violence to major international events,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Buell </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION>'s assistant general manager for news photos. `` He was one of the early enthusiasts who helped lead the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> into its present all-color photo