<HEAD>Observers Call Salvadoran Elections Free and Fair</HEAD>
<UNK>With PM-Salvador, Bjt</UNK>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> observers called <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON>'s presidential election a success despite widespread violence and a rebel intimidation campaign. `` Based upon our observations, our determination is that the election was free and fair,'' the 21-member delegation said in a report released late Sunday. The presidential commission arrived in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> on Saturday and was to leave today. They visited about 50 of the nation's 262 precincts. `` I think I'll call it a successful election. It was n't peaceful, but it was successful,'' Sen. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON>, R-Ky., the delegation chariman, told a news conference Sunday evening after the polls closed <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> praised the voting as a victory over leftist rebels who have been at war with the U.S.-backed government for nine years. `` This nation wants to govern itself with the most powerful ammunition there is: the vote,'' the Republican governor said. Despite widespread fighting between government troops and the guerrillas, the observers were never exposed to combat or attack, officials said. The observers said they talked to voters, election workers and soldiers. `` What we have observed in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> is a passionate commitment of a people to participate in the democratic process despite being faced with: intimidation, threats, violence and death from persons outside the political process,'' the report said. Still, observer <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Doherty </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> said rebel intimidation hindered the voting. `` We have still got a long way to go until we call this a democracy,'' he said. The White House named the official delegation of <ORGANIZATION> congress </ORGANIZATION> members, state politicans and private citizens. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> selected the precincts the observers visited by motorcade and helicopter. Earlier in the day, delegation members said the balloting appeared to be conducted under conditions designed to prevent fraud. <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said the rebels `` did n't stop a lot of people voting today. We saw nothing but essentially a civic fiesta.'' Delegation member Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON>, R-Calif., said he welcomed a victory by the right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, or <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, over the incumbent <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> `` Now I see that the momentum has changed to the Arena party,'' <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON> said. `` I'm a conservative. It's time for my guys to win.'' Rep. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>, D-Calif., said <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> supporters apparently turned out strongly, lining up at polling stations in the capital and countryside `` It looks like they -LRB- the voters -RRB- were chosen by the Arena party,'' he said. <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said disputes may arise in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> after the election because current policies have not brought an end to the war and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will need to debate whether military and economic aid to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> should continue at present levels.
