<HEAD>Special Congressional Election Campaign Enters Final Two Weeks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS P. WYMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WAYNE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A political game of musical chairs has some Republicans fearing they could be left standing in the cold while the Democrats plop into a <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> congressional seat. On March 28, for the second time in less than five months, voters will elect a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> representative from northeast <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>'s 4th District. Last November, the seat was again a Republican shoo-in, little-watched as political interests focused on closer races. The good fortune of two <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> Republicans, however, may have changed that. With the election of <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> to the vice presidency and the appointment of incumbent Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON> to fill <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s vacated <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat, Republicans were forced to pick a special election candidate from a field of relative unknowns. Against the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> choice, the Democrats already had decided to run <PERSON> Jill </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, a candidate with a mixed resume. Long already had lost two races for federal office, both by wide margins: <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> defeated her in 1986 to win a second <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> term and Coats repeated the drubbing in 1988 for his fifth House term. The Republicans picked <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Heath </PERSON>, a 36-year-old aide to <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmke </PERSON>. <PERSON> Heath </PERSON>, an attorney with <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> experience as a member of Coats' staff, had never sought elective office. He began the campaign largely unrecognized outside <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, where he had served <PERSON> Helmke </PERSON>'s administration as public safety director, Republicans con