<HEAD>Dollar Mixed, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar was mixed in thin European trading today. Gold prices were little changed. Foreign currency dealers said interest in dollar-buying was dampened by fears of central bank intervention. Central banks in several <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries reportedly intervened in the currency markets on Thursday and Friday. `` It's very quiet,'' said a trader at a large West German bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>. `` I do n't think the dollar is going to do much today. I think, if anything, we're at the top of the range now.'' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.85 yen to a closing 131.92. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 131.80 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday: _ 1.8749 West German marks, down from 1.8770 _ 1.6155 Swiss francs, up from 1.6140 _ 6.3465 French francs, up from 6.3450 _ 2.1146 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1145 _ 1,375.00 Italian lire, down from 1,376.25 _ 1.1953 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1965 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.7137, slightly more expensive for buyers Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 395 a troy ounce, up from $ 393.25 bid late Friday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 395.30. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 393, unchanged from late Friday's bid price Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold rose $ 1.94 to close at a bid $ 396.81. Silver was quoted in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 6.17 a troy ounce, up from Friday's $ 6.14.
