<HEAD>Soviet Magazine Prints Essay by Solzhenitsyn</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 5th graf pvs `moreover, the...' to ADD circulation of publication;
pickup 6th graf pvs `The 2{-page...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small circulation Soviet magazine has printed an essay <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> wrote shortly before he was forced into exile in which he appeals to his countrymen to cast off officially-sanctioned lies. The magazine also carried a commentary crediting the Nobel laureate for helping prepare the way for President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. The publication represents another step in the gradual rehabilitation of an author whose major works remain banned in his homeland. However, the magazine did not publish <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s most trenchent criticisms of Soviet politics, including his charge that repression has been a key element of <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> policy since the days of <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lenin </PERSON>. Moreover, the essay was printed in a magazine destined in part for foreign markets, selling 50,000 copies abroad in Russian, English, French, Spanish and German, and with only a 100,000-copy circulation at home. The 2 -LCB- - page essay `` Live Not by Lies! was published in the February bulletin of the officially sanctioned <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Peace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>'s monthly, Twentieth Century and Peace. It was written shortly before <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> was arrested and expelled from the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> for his writings. In the essay, which was circulated at the time in thousands of illegal self-published copies, <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> called on his countrymen to display courage and resist pressure from the country's rulers. An honest man, wrote <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>, `` does not raise his hand to vote for a proposal that he does not sincerely sympathize with, does not vote either openly or in secret for a person he believes is unworthy or doubtful.'' That sort of language, considered anti-Soviet and seditious under President <PERSON> Leonid </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brezhnev </PERSON>'s rule in the 1970s, is now fully in line with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s calls for greater openness, civic responsibility and democracy. Author <PERSON> Igor </PERSON> <PERSON> Vinogradov </PERSON>, in the commentary appended to <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s essay, called the arrest and banishment of the 1970 Nobel Prize winner `` a shameful act'' and lauded the writer's `` high spiritual and civic courage.'' Without such brave people who spoke out against abuses of the Soviet rulers of their time, <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s drive for `` perestroika,'' social and economic reforms, may never have come about, <PERSON> Vinogradov </PERSON> said. `` Those changes which started in our country three years ago _ could they be possible if in our society, in all its strata, contempt and loathing had not ripened among nearly everyone for those who personified the ruling evil and violence, and for their miserable servants, flooding the country with lies and demagoguery?'' he wrote. In an interview published today by <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Natalia </PERSON>, who often speaks for him, said she was disappointed that the essay was published in such a small-circulation journal because the piece was written as a broad, national appeal. `` Given that this was meant as an address to the people, this is not the place it should be published,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> was quoted as saying in a telephone interview from her home in <LOCATION> Cavendish </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Vt. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Vadim </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s ideology chief, said late last year he favored a continued ban on publishing works by <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> because they would undermine Soviet society `` I am against the publication of a number of works by <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON> and in the first place such works as ` <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>' and ` The Gulag Archipelago,'' the Politburo member told a Nov. 29 news conference `` To publish <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s works would mean to, in effect, undermine the foundations on which today's life rests,'' <PERSON> Medvedev </PERSON> said. His remarks indicated there are still limits on the amount of openness allowed under <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s reforms. <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s `` One Day in the Life of <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Denisovich </PERSON>,'' a chronicle of life in Soviet labor camps under dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, was published in 1962 during the thaw allowed by <PERSON> Nikita </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Khrushchev </PERSON> following <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s death. Some Soviet writers, artists and activists have clamored for the publication of <PERSON> Solzhenitsyn </PERSON>'s works and his return to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. In October, the filmmakers' union asked for a review of his 1974 expulsion.
