<FIRST>r a PM-AppleControversy     03-20 0657</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Apple Controversy,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anatomy of a Chemical Scare: TV, Celebrity Bring Issue to Fore</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GARTIES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The farm chemical Alar has for four years been a symbol of industrial arrogance and regulatory foot-dragging to followers of the consumer movement. But despite activists' efforts, it's a safe bet most Americans knew little or nothing about Alar, which is used to grow crisper, more colorful apples, and which has been linked to cancer in animal tests. That's changed dramatically in the last two weeks. The Alar-apple debate quickly gained public-policy star status through a `` 60 Minutes'' television report, the involvement of actress Meryl Streep and surprise moves by educators in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> to yank apples from school lunchrooms. Despite reassurances from the government and health establishment that Alar is n't all that unsafe, signs of alarm have mounted: _ By the end of last week, the heads of the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> both felt compelled to defend the nation's apple supply They were joined by Surgeon General <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Koop </PERSON>, who released a statement Saturday saying: `` I wish to send a message to mothers across the country: It's OK, Mom, apples are good for your kids!''' _ Apple growers in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state blamed the controversy for a drop of nearly 10 percent in shipments of apples out of state in two weeks _ Grocers and apple processing companies across the country reiterated policies against accepting apples sprayed with Alar Meanwhile, the manufacturer of the chemical, <ORGANIZATION> Uniroyal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Middlebury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, has repeatedly cited research showing Alar in the concentrations found in apples does n't pose a cancer threat. The Alar debate has been around with varying degrees of fervor since August 1985, when the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> considered but rejected a ban on the chemical, used to control ripening and improve quality, consistency and shelf life of apples. In early February, the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> finally did propose a phaseout of use of the chemical, which would take it off the market starting probably next year. But the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the threat of Alar was not so severe that the ban had to start right away. Consumer groups, including <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Nader </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, have campaigned for an immediate ban instead. The periodic consumer campaigns have prompted many big supermarket chains and apple processors across the country to quit accepting Alar-treated apples. As a result, use of the chemical fell to an estimated 5 percent to 10 percent of the crop from a high around 50 percent. Many growers hoped controversy was behind them. But on Feb. 26, the dormant controversy erupted anew. The <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> television show `` 60 Minutes'' reported a study by the Natural Resources group suggesting children, because of low body weight and proportionately high consumption of apples, had a heightened risk of cancer from Alar. Then Miss Streep appeared on TV talk shows and gave interviews about her fears for her three children's health. The resulting blast of publicity prompted officials in the nation's two biggest school districts, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, to temporarily pull apples and apple products from their cafeterias. Reports of the apple bans quickly spread. `` In our democratic process, an angry mob will be listened to no matter what the facts are,'' said <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Helmke </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, consultant with the <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lake </PERSON>, <PERSON> Lerer </PERSON> and <PERSON> Montgomery </PERSON> public relations firm. `` That's what's happened in this case _ this story has struck a nerve,'' <PERSON> Helmke </PERSON> said. Studies show Alar, a trade name for the chemical daminozide, could be linked to cancer in laboratory animals. A breakdown product of Alar called <ORGANIZATION> UDMH </ORGANIZATION> also was shown to cause cancer when give to test animals in large amounts. The American <ORGANIZATION> Academy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pediatrics </ORGANIZATION> adopted a position paper March 11 calling for an end to Alar use but said parents should n't worry about farm chemicals applied in legal amounts.
</TEXT>
