<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 5th graf `The only...' to move up reference
to Deng not attending, provide additional detail on on leaders, seating
arrangement. Pickup 6th graf `The tone...'; DELETES 12th graf pvs `Sitting
behind...' to remove redundant material.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> opened the annual session of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s legislature today by calling on Chinese to work harder and make more financial sacrifices to collectively overcome worsening economic woes. `` Both government and people should be mentally prepared for a few years of austerity,'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> told more than 2,000 delegates at the Great Hall of the People in central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. He urged officials to give up their `` vested interests in favor of the interests of the whole. `` If we set a good example and explain clearly to the people the need for tightening our belts, they will surely understand and support it,'' he said. The only exceptions <PERSON> Li </PERSON> made to the tight-money policy were agriculture and education. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said the education budget would be increased and more loans would be made to farmers. Sitting behind <PERSON> Li </PERSON> on the rostrum were other government and Communist Party leaders. Senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, 84, was absent, but there was no official explanation. <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> attended last year's opening session. The chair normally filled by <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, next to <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, was filled by President <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> <PERSON> Shangkun </PERSON>. Next to <PERSON> Yang </PERSON> sat <PERSON> Li </PERSON> and next to him sat Vice Premier <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zheng </PERSON>. Two chairs were empty. The tone of <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s speech contrasted with last year's, when he called for bold new efforts to move the economy away from rigid central planning that long stifled growth. Since then, however, inflation has climbed to a post-war record annual rate of 36 percent, and overheated demand has caused shortages, hoarding and several bank runs. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> blamed the economic problems on `` a tendency to be too impatient for quick results. `` More often than not we tended to ignore the fact that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has a huge population, is relatively short of resources and has an unevenly developed economy,'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said in a criticism of policies that he helped shape. `` We ... did not pay sufficient attention to taking comprehensive and coordinated measures and failed to tighten control and supervision at the right moment,'' he said. `` We were too optimistic.'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> was interrupted by applause when he reaffirmed <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s claim to sovereignty over <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and denounced foreign support of Tibetan separatism as `` outrageous interference in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s internal affairs.'' He also reiterated <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s position that it was justified in imposing martial law in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> on March 8 after three days of anti-Chinese violence in which at least 12 people died. <LOCATION> Tibetan </LOCATION> activists claim the region was independent before the Communist takeover in 1950. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> did not mention letters sent to the congress by more than 100 intellectuals appealing for an amnesty for political prisoners, or the growing public clamor for greater freedom of speech. Most of <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s speech was devoted to economic problems and austerity measures, including strengthening control over price increases, loans and new construction. However, he said the state would increase its grain purchase price by 18 percent beginning April 1 in an effort to end a four-year slump in production. Banks will increase agricultural loans, he said. `` Agriculture stands out as the weakest link in the national economy at present,'' he said. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> also announced a 15 percent increase in the education budget, to $ 10 billion. `` This figure is the best the government can do under the present tight budget, although it still falls far short of actual needs,'' he said. He said alternate sources of funding would have to be found. The congress meets through April 4 to hear more government reports and discuss proposed laws. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> delegates are elected by provincial congresses, which in turn are chosen by municipal and county congresses in each area. Citizens actually vote only for representatives in the lowest-level local congress.
