<HEAD>Ten People Convicted for Philadelphia Abortion Demonstration Lose
Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten people criminally convicted for their participation in a 1985 protest demonstration at a <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> abortion clinic lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today. The justices, without comment, refused to hear arguments that the defendants wrongly were barred from asserting medical justification as a defense for their crimes. The appeal also urged that the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> case be used to reverse the high court's 1973 decision legalizing abortion. The justices already have under study an abortion-regulation dispute from <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> in which they are being asked to reverse or limit the 16-year-old ruling in a case called <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>. In the <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> case, the 10 were convicted of `` defiant trespass'' and acquitted of all other charges stemming from an Aug. 10, 1985, anti-abortion demonstration at the Northeast Women's Center A state appeals court said the 10 `` pushed their way'' into the clinic and occupied several rooms. `` Once inside, they damaged two aspirator machines and other medical instruments, threw equipment out of a third-floor window and placed ` pro-life' stickers on the doors, walls and ceilings,'' the state court said. After refusing to leave, the 10 protesters were carried away by police officers. Each drew a sentence of one day to three months in jail. A state appeals court upheld the convictions and sentences last May 2, and the <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to hear their appeal last Oct. 20. In the appeal acted on today, lawyers for the 10 protesters said their clients are among `` thousands of law-abiding citizens ... now engaging in heightened demonstrations or ` rescues' at abortion clinics throughout the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' The appeal said that each of the protesters `` knew that his or her conduct would otherwise be criminal except for the defense of justification sought to be interposed in this case.'' The appeal was filed in behalf of <PERSON> Roland </PERSON> <PERSON> Markum </PERSON>, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Walton </PERSON>, <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Silcox </PERSON>, <PERSON> Kathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Breen </PERSON>, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tenagolio </PERSON>, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Gies </PERSON>. The case is <PERSON> Markum </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, 88-1218.
