<HEAD>FLorida Company Loses Appeal in Weekly Devotional Services Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Florida-based company wanting to require all its employees to attend weekly <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> devotional services lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today. The justices, without comment, left intact rulings that the requirement violated the rights of an atheist who worked at the company's plant in <LOCATION> Eloy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. Lawyers for the company argued that its owners' constitutionally protected religious freedoms were violated `` Unless ... employers -LRB- may -RRB- operate their businesses in accordance with their sincerely held religious beliefs, the private workplace will increasingly become void of religion,'' the appeal contended. J.O. -LRB- <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> -RRB- and <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Townley </PERSON> control and manage the <ORGANIZATION> Townley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Candler </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla </LOCATION>. The couple are born-again Christians who said they promised God their mining-equipment manufacturing company `` would be a Christian, faith-operated business.'' The company, founded in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> in 1963, since has opened other plants, including one in <LOCATION> Eloy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>. Employees at <LOCATION> Townley </LOCATION> plants for years were required to attend weekly devotional services <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Pelvas </PERSON>, identified in court documents as an atheist, began working as a machinist at the <LOCATION> Townley </LOCATION> plant in <LOCATION> Eloy </LOCATION> in 1979. Mandatory attendance at devotional services was not required there until 1984. <PERSON> Pelvas </PERSON> attended several and then asked to be excused because he was an atheist. His supervisor told <PERSON> Pelvas </PERSON> that he had to attend but that he could sleep, read a newspaper or otherwise engage himself durng the services. <PERSON> Pelvas </PERSON> continued to attend the services, which usually lasted 30 to 45 minutes during the work day, but in October 1984 he filed a religious-discrimination complaint with the <ORGANIZATION> federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Equal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opportunity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Pelvas </PERSON> left the company two months later, saying he was offered a transfer that amounted to a firing. The commission in 1986 ruled that <PERSON> Townley </PERSON> violated a part of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 barring on-the-job religious discrimination. A federal trial judge in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> barred <PERSON> Townley </PERSON> in May 1987 from continuing mandatory devotional services at the Eloy plant. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the judge's injunction last Oct. 20 The appeals court noted that the federal law imposes a duty on employers to accommodate an employee's religious practices unless doing so would cause undue hardship. The appeals court said <PERSON> Townley </PERSON> had failed to prove any undue hardship in <LOCATION> Pelvas </LOCATION>' case, and rejected the company's argument that it is a `` religious corporation'' <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> intended to exempt from the law. `` The <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION> does not seek to enjoin the services altogether; rather it only objects to their mandatory nature,'' the appeals court said. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration urged the court to rule against <PERSON> Townley </PERSON> and its owners. `` Any minor burden on the Townleys' religious practices is justified in this case,'' government lawyers said. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Townley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> EEOC </ORGANIZATION>, 88-988.
