<HEAD>Court Turns Away Milk Antitrust Dispute </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today turned away a still-pending, big-money antitrust dispute over the sale of raw milk. The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling that could cost millions for two cooperative associations of dairy farmers and a marketing agent for dairy cooperatives. The case is nearly 18 years old, dating back to a 1971 lawsuit filed by one of the dairy cooperatives who ended up an unsuccessful defendant in a counter-suit. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 ruled against <ORGANIZATION> Mid-America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dairymen </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. The appeals court said they had engaged in a broad, illegal conspiracy to eliminate competitive sellers of Grade A raw milk in the Midwest. The appeals court ruled that the conspiracy hurt the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a nationwide farm bargaining organization. The 8th Circuit court's 1982 ruling instructed <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, to determine what monetary damages <ORGANIZATION> NFO </ORGANIZATION> should collect. In ensuing proceedings before Judge <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NFO </ORGANIZATION> advanced alternative damage measurement theories. It claimed tripled damages of $ 55.4 million under one theory, and tripled damages of $ 22.2 million under the other. The trial judge refused to award any damages. Ruling in the case a second time last July 6, the <ORGANIZATION> 8th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> court </ORGANIZATION> reaffirmed its holding that <ORGANIZATION> NFO </ORGANIZATION> `` incurred substantial damages'' as a result of illegal acts. The appeals court again sent the case back to <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON>, with `` more specific directions ... with respect to the computation of damages.'' The appeals court also said the trial judge should `` determine and award appropriate attorneys fees and costs'' to <ORGANIZATION> NFO </ORGANIZATION>. It said <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> was right in rejecting the theory under which <ORGANIZATION> NFO </ORGANIZATION> said it was entitled to $ 55.4 million. But it said the theory under which <ORGANIZATION> NFO </ORGANIZATION> claimed $ 22.2 million in damages `` is a proper basis for a substantial damage award.'' The cases are <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1247, and <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> vs. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Farmers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1248.
