<HEAD>Court Refuses to Let States Be Sued in California Copyright Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today again refused to let states and state agencies be sued for allegedly violating federal copyright laws. The justices, without comment, refused to revive allegations that <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state-run university, illegally copied a company's computer programs and instruction manuals. The justices on Feb. 21 turned away a similar appeal by a photographer who accused a state university in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> of unauthorized use of his photographs. In the case acted on today, BV Engineering's appeal was supported by numerous members of the artistic, entertainment and literary community. Nine major motion picture studios urged the court to hear BV Engineering's appeal to broaden protection against what they said is widespread copyright infringement. The movie producers said, for example, that prisons in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> are refusing to pay for films shown to inmates. BV Engineering sued <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> in 1986, accusing the university of illegally copying seven computer programs and the accompanying user manuals. The suit was thrown out by a federal judge, and the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled last October that states and state agencies are immune from copyright-infringement suits. The appeals court said states are protected by the Constitution's 11th Amendment, which shields them from a variety of lawsuits The appeals court, citing previous <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings, said the federal Copyright Act of 1976 does not explicitly remove _ or abrogate _ the 11th Amendment protection. `` We are constrained by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>'s mandate that we find an abrogation of 11th Amendment immunity only when <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has included in the statute unequivocal and specific language indicating an intent to subject states to suit in federal court,'' the 9th Circuit court said. `` We recognize that our holding will allow states to violate the federal copyright laws with virtual impunity,'' the appeals court continued. `` It is for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, however, to remedy this problem.'' BV Engineering said it was left without a remedy since federal copyright law bars the company from suing <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION> in state court in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. The case is BV Engineering vs. <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1099.
