<HEAD>IRS Worker Goes Public With Complaint; Gore Promises Protection</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employee who, under a cloak of anonymity, accused the agency of not telling people who neglect to subtract withholding when figuring their taxes went public on network television today and was promised protection by Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> `` If they try any kind of reprisal, they better watch out'' <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>, D-Tenn., said of <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employee, <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, a return examiner in the agency's service center in <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, appeared with <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Today'' show She had planned to appear in silhouette and with her voice disguised, but dropped those precautions because `` I found out that it's probabaly known out there ... who has actually reported it,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> originally told her story during a private meeting with <PERSON> Gore </PERSON>. She repeated it in an interview with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> last week, but insisted that she not be identifed at the time because of fear of retaliation. She is involved in the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION>'s program to detect taxpayers who fail to report some or all their taxable income. About 15 months after tax returns are filed, computers match returns with Form 1099s, W-2s and other source-of-income reports and if some income does not show up on a return, examiners such as Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> decide whether the taxpayer should be sent a letter demanding an explanation. In 1987, while checking 1985 returns, Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said, she and colleagues found numerous returns on which filers had failed to subtract withheld taxes from taxes owed. That meant the taxpayers were overpaying. When she went to supervisors, she said, they told her <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> policy required taxpayers to find their own mistakes. After protests, she added, her superiors checked with <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> headquarters in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and were told to abide by the policy. `` It was stealing from the taxpayers,'' Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said. She said the disputed policy was changed last year to allow <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> employees to notify taxpayers when they fail to subtract taxes that have been withheld from wages or periodic pension payments. But the old policy still stands for taxpayers who neglect to subtract taxes withheld from lump-sum pension payments. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> has steadfastly refused to comment directly on Ms. <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>'s assertions, saying it is reviewing its employee manual and policies. However, in an appearance before the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> oversight subcommittee last week, acting <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said `` it is possible that taxpayers did not get the refund they were entitled to.'' Even after changes were made last December, <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said, `` I still am not completely satisfied with that program.''
