<HEAD>Court Refuses to Bar Oklahoma Prosecutors From Forcing Removal of
Bullet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to bar <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> prosecutors who seek incriminating evidence from forcing the surgical removal of a bullet from a murder suspect's arm. The court, without comment, turned down <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>' arguments that removing the bullet would violate his constitutional protection against unreasonable searches and seizures The <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Criminal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, by a 2-1 vote last Oct. 27, ruled that the surgery could be peformed against <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>' will. The operation has not yet taken place. Andrews is charged with first-degree murder in the March 3, 1988, shooting death of <PERSON> Hatten </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Ledford </PERSON> in rural <LOCATION> McClain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>. Before he died, <PERSON> Ledford </PERSON> told someone he thought he had wounded the man who shot him, whom he identified as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miser </PERSON>. <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> was found, suffering from a gunshot wound, about 750 feet from <PERSON> Ledford </PERSON>'s home. A state judge approved county prosecutors' request to compel surgical removal of the bullet lodged in Andrews' upper arm. The state appeals court, in upholding that ruling, noted a doctor's testimony for prosecutors that removal of the bullet would not be life-threatening, and would require only a local anesthetic. `` The extent of the surgical intrusion upon the defendant's protective interests, privacy ... personal dignity and body integrity is not impermissibly significant,'' the state appeals court ruled In the appeal acted on today, <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON> argued that the <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> court's decision conflicts with what the justices ruled in a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> case four years ago. In the 1985 decision, the high court refused to let <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> law enforcement officials force the surgical removal of a bullet from a criminal suspect's chest. `` A compelled surgical intrusion into an individual's body for evidence ... implicates expectations of privacy and security of such magnitude that the intrusion may be unreasonable even if likely to produce evidence of a crime,'' the court said in the 1985 case. The justices in that decision drew a distinction between the surgical removal of a bullet and the taking, over a suspect's protest, of a blood sample to establish intoxication The court allowed such takings of blood samples in a 1966 ruling. The <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> court, distinguishing <PERSON> Andrews </PERSON>' case from the 1985 decision, said the surgery required in the <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> case was riskier. The case is Andrews vs. Love, 88-1296.
