<TEXT>
 A newspaper photographer convicted for pursuing a police chase and photographing a suspect's arrest in <LOCATION> Troy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, three years ago lost a <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> appeal today. The court, without comment, left intact <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>'s conviction on charges of obstructing police work <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, also convicted of reckless driving in connection with the May 6, 1986, incident, was sentenced to five days in jail and fined $ 400. His appeal did not challenge the reckless-driving conviction. But the appeal attacked a Troy city ordinance that states no one `` shall obstruct, resist, hinder or oppose'' any police officer's duties <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>'s lawyers said the ordinance, when invoked against him, violated free-press rights. They also argued that the ordinance should be struck down because `` it places unfettered enforcement discretion in the hands of the police.'' <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON>, then working as an intern photographer for The <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, was driving along <ORGANIZATION> Interstate </ORGANIZATION> 75 when he heard on his radio that a nearby police car was pursuing a car that had rammed it. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> pulled onto the highway shoulder and waited until he saw a state police car chasing another car. He then followed, driving up to 80 miles an hour to stay right behind the state trooper's car. When the suspect's car came to a stop, the state trooper stopped his patrol car right behind it, jumped out and drew his gun. Troy police also had guns drawn and pointed at the suspect. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> photographed the tense scene, from what his lawyers said was about 10 feet away. But lawyers for the city told the justices that <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> was as close at 18 inches to the suspect, and that he refused to get out of the way when ordered to do so by police. <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> no longer lives in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, his lawyer said, but still works as a newspaper photographer. He has not yet completed the 5-day sentence, or paid the $ 400 fine. The case is <PERSON> Hoffman </PERSON> vs. Troy, 88-1212.
