<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today rejected an appeal by workers at a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> nuclear power plant who are challenging their employer's random drug tests. The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that threw out, at least temporarily, a lawsuit attacking the tests. The justices already are studying the validity of drug tests in three other cases, one involving a private employer and two concerning federal workers or federal regulations. The case acted on today stems from tests initiated by <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> at its <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Onofre </LOCATION> nuclear plant. The tests, modified in December 1986, require randomly selected workers to produce urine samples for laboratory analysis. The workers are told the day before they are tested. The plan was challenged by Local 246 of the <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION>. The union said the tests violate the collective bargaining agreement between the workers and the utility, and also violate provisions of the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Constitution protecting privacy and freedom from unreasonable searches and seizure. The union's lawsuit was filed in state court and transferred to a federal court at the request of <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION>. A federal judge in 1987 temporarily blocked the tests pending resolution of a grievance filed by the union. But the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> overturned the judge's injunction, and also ruled that the lawsuit was preempted by federal labor law The appeals court said the federal Labor Management Relations Act governing worker-employer disputes bars the nuclear plant workers from filing a suit now claiming their rights guaranteed by the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Constitution were violated. `` Drug testing does not implicate the sort of non-negotiable state-law rights'' that would allow the suit to be decided in court before it is determined whether the tests violate the workers' collective bargaining agreement, the appeals court said The appeals court said the next step for the union is to submit the case to arbitration to decide whether the contract was violated because the utility unilaterally adopted the tests. The appeals court did not rule out the possibility that Local 246 could return to the courts if it loses in arbitration. The union said it should be entitled now to a ruling on whether the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Constitution protects workers against random drug tests. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1180.
