<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two women active in fighting pornography today lost <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> attempts to revive libel lawsuits against Hustler magazine and its publisher, <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynt </PERSON>. The court, without comment, let stand rulings that 1985 articles villifying each woman in pornographic terms are constitutionally protected expressions of opinion. <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Ault </PERSON>, who founded an anti-pornography group in <LOCATION> Milwaukie </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Dorchen </PERSON> <PERSON> Leidholdt </PERSON>, a New Yorker who helped found Women Against Pornography, were the targets of a column published each month in Hustler. The column, which frequently elicits libel suits from its subjects, singles out people who oppose the sexually explicit magazine's views. Carrying an epithet as its title, the column usually engages in personal attacks as well as criticizing its targets' views. Ms. <PERSON> Ault </PERSON> was the column's target in the magazine's April 1985 issue; Ms. <PERSON> Leidholdt </PERSON> in the June 1985 edition. Some of the gentler terms used to describe Ms. <PERSON> Ault </PERSON> included `` fanatic,'' `` crackpot,'' `` threatened by sex'' and `` deluded busybody.'' Ms. <PERSON> Leidholdt </PERSON>'s lawsuit charged that the June 1985 column falsely described her as `` sexually repressed,'' a person who hates men and herself and suffers from `` bizarre paranoia,'' `` vengeful hysteria,'' and `` demented thinking.'' Ms. <PERSON> Ault </PERSON> sued in federal court in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>; Ms. <PERSON> Leidholdt </PERSON> in federal court in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>. Both suits were dismissed by a trial judge before they reached a jury, and the 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the dismissals last October. In Ms. <PERSON> Ault </PERSON>'s case, the appeals court said, `` We think it clear that there is a heated and spirited debate on pornography of which this article is a part, in which epithets, fiery rhetoric and hyperbole are expected.'' The appeals court added, `` It is unfortunate that the legal category of opinion must be used to describe a statement that is no more than a vicious slur but base and malignant speech is not necessarily actionable -LRB- libel -RRB-.'' In the appeals acted on today, lawyers for both women argued that the <ORGANIZATION> 9th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> court rulings unduly expanded the concept of legally protected expressions of opinion. `` What public debate is furthered by this type of assault on personal dignity?'' one appeal asked. `` Elevation of such conduct to the pedestal of protected speech should not be tolerated.'' But lawyers for <PERSON> Flynt </PERSON> and his magazine, in urging that the appeals be rejected, argued that the Constitution protects even `` vituperative, pejorative or pernicious opinion.'' The cases are <PERSON> Leidholdt </PERSON> vs. L.F.P. <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1214, and <ORGANIZATION> Ault </ORGANIZATION> v. <ORGANIZATION> Hustler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 88-1215.
