<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to revive a libel lawsuit against the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> by a <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> commander court-martialed in 1984 after his ship ran aground in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. The justices, citing a lack of jurisdiction, left intact <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> court decisions dismissing Cmdr. <PERSON> Willard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> -LRB- Bud -RRB- <PERSON> Chrisman </PERSON>'s suit that alleged seven Times articles ruined his Naval career. The state courts cited <PERSON> Chrisman </PERSON>'s failure to request a correction or retraction, a requirement under state libel law, and the legal protection given to fair and accurate reports of governmental proceedings. The first sued-over article reported allegations that <PERSON> Chrisman </PERSON> had been intoxicated when his ship, the San Diego-based <LOCATION> USS </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Thomaston </LOCATION>, ran aground in <LOCATION> Port </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Allen </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kauai </LOCATION>, on Jan. 24, 1984. The second article reported that the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> had decided to court-martial <PERSON> Chrisman </PERSON> on charges stemming from the grounding. The last five articles reported on each day of the court-martial, concluding with a report that <PERSON> Chrisman </PERSON> had been convicted of negligently hazarding his ship but acquitted of charges that he was drunk at the time. A state trial judge refused to dismiss <PERSON> Chrisman </PERSON>'s suit against the Times, but an appeals court later ordered that the case be thrown out. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> refused to hear <PERSON> Chrisman </PERSON>'s appeal last July 28. In the appeal acted on today, <PERSON> Ch