<HEAD>Court Refuses to Let Idaho Officials Tax Income of Some Railway Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today refused to let <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> officials tax the income of railway workers who live elsewhere but pass through the state as crew members on non-stop freight trains. The court, without comment, let stand a ruling that such a tax would violate the Constitution and be unfair to the workers. The <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled last May that <ORGANIZATION> Burlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> crews working on trains traveling between <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Whitefish </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Missoula </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mont. </LOCATION>, may not be forced to pay the tax. The trains cross <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s panhandle without making any scheduled stops in the state. <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> officials in 1983 ordered the railway workers to pay taxes on income received from 1978 through 1982. The state sought to impose the tax on a portion of the workers' income state officials said was earned while in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>. The state <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said, `` <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> is not the source of this income since there is no contribution by <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> to the production of this income. It would be unfair to allow the state to impose a tax on the income of the train crews earned while they are merely passing through <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>.'' The state court said the tax violates the Constitution by interfering with interstate commerce and by denying the workers due process protection. The state court added that the workers' wages while passing through <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> `` are not attributable to any economic activity within <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> markets and commerce do not affect their income in any degree.'' The state court relied largely on <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> rulings holding that the test for the constitutionality of a state tax affecting out-of-state residents is `` whether the state has given anything for which it can ask return.'' The state Court said while the state has given something of value to <LOCATION> Burlington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION>, it `` has not given anything to the train crews for which it can ask return.'' In the appeal acted on today, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> officials said the state court ruling `` sets a dangerous and disruptive precedent'' and conflicts with decisions by other courts giving states sweeping power to tax non-residents who work within those states. `` Taxpayers in other jurisdictions are now lining up to challenge taxation of non-residents based on <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>'s decision,'' the state's appeal said The case is <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tax </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> vs. Blangers, 88-1266.
