<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today agreed to use a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> case to decide whether federal courts may make it easier to broaden age discrimination lawsuits against employers. The court said it will hear an appeal by <ORGANIZATION> Hoffmann-La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which is accused of bias against older workers in laying off some 1,200 employees at <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> plants. The company dismissed the employees on Feb. 4, 1985. A group of older workers, who called the day `` Black Monday'' for many veteran <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> workers, said a disproportionately high number of those laid off was over age 40. The group filed a federal lawsuit, charging the company with violating the federal Age Discrimination in Employment Act. The group's leaders then sought to contact all fired <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> employees over 40 eligible to join the so-called class-action lawsuit. Some 400 employees agreed to join. But the leaders of the court battle against the company said they believed there may be 200 additional fired workers who are members of the class allegedly victimized by age discrimination. The leaders sought to contact the potentially missing workers by direct-mail and notices posted at <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> plants. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> authorized the employees' group, once the missing workers are found, to provide them with an explanation of the suit and a form that would allow them to join the suit <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> officials appealed the ruling, arguing that <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON> exceeded his authority. But the 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> upheld the judge's decision. `` There is no legal impediment to court-authorized notice in an appropriate case'' where those who have filed a class-action suit are seeking other potential plaintiffs, the appeals court said. `` We assume that the district courts will exercise caution that notices approved by the courts will not give the erroneous impression that maintenance of the action has a judicial imprimatur of approval.'' An increased number of plaintiffs in such suits can be a big advantage because it spreads out the court costs. In seeking workers to join the suit, the leaders of the court fight asked for _ but did not require _ a $ 200 contribution to help defray the costs. In appealing to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hoffman-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> officials noted that federal appeals courts elsewhere have disagreed with the 3rd Circuit court decision. The officials urged the high court to clear up the confusion. The case is <PERSON> Hoffmann-La </PERSON> <PERSON> Roche </PERSON> vs. <PERSON> Sperling </PERSON>, 88-1203.
