 About 200 police raided eight government ministries Monday in an investigation into whether state workers are regularly absent, have second jobs or falsely claim sick days, news reports said. Employees found guilty of unjustifiable absenteeism will be charged with aggravated fraud, and their bosses may also face charges. A state magistrate ordered the investigation after citizens complained about chronic absenteeism among state employees, and several news reports appeared on the subject. The police confiscated documents from the ministries of Culture, Education, Health, Foreign Trade, Tourism, <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Merchant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> and Budget. The Interior and Finance minsitries will be investigated separately, according to reports from news agencies and television.
