<HEAD>Five Killed In Civil War Fighting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to update casualties, details on fighting.
Picks up 6th graf pvs ``The clashes pitted...'' </HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Christian and Moslem forces battled today with heavy artillery and tanks in the capital and the surrounding hills. Police said five people were killed and 15 wounded. The casualties increased the toll to 54 people killed and 179 wounded on the 13th day of the latest round of fighting in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war Also today, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> warplanes bombed what <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> said were <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> bases of the pro-Syrian Popular Front for the <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Palestine-General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, a faction of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. Police said six fighter bombers carried out the raid on the town of <LOCATION> Bar </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Elias </LOCATION>, killing six people and wounding nine. The Israeli attack came amid continuing artillery clashes between Christian and Moslem gunners who pounded residential districts on both sides of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s dividing Green Line. A police spokesman said five people, including an army officer, were killed and 15 wounded, four of them soldiers. The spokesman, who can not be identified under standing regulations, said the Christian and Moslem forces battled with tanks and heavy artillery around Souk el-Gharb, an army garrison town 15 miles southeast of the capital. Shells fell on at least 10 residential neighborhoods on both sides of the frontline in <LOCATION> Souk </LOCATION> <LOCATION> el-Gharb </LOCATION>, the spokesman said. He said shells also hit the Christian ports of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Jounieh </LOCATION> and the airport highway in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. The airport has been closed since March 11. The clashes pitted predominantly <ORGANIZ