<HEAD>Judge Stops City From Enforcing Teen Curfew</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge today stopped the <LOCATION> District </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Columbia </LOCATION> from enforcing the city's new emergency curfew law for teen-agers. After a hearing on a suit brought by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> issued a 10-day temporary restraining order blocking enforcement of the statute. In issuing his ruling, the judge said the law was too broad. He noted that Mayor <PERSON> Marion </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> has said alternative legislation will be proposed to narrow the law. <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> said he would extend the restraining order if <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s legislation does not differ from the emergency bill reviewed today <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>'s revised measure is expected to go to the <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday or next week. The law went into effect last Thursday but <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> delayed enforcement of the measure until Monday night to give police time to become familiar with its provisions and to inform the public. <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Spitzer </PERSON> said the law would penalize youths and also could give them a permanent legal record. City attorneys, however, argued that parents would be penalized. But, <PERSON> Richey </PERSON> noted that the students' names would be entered into a permanent police record which might affect their ability to get jobs. The <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> filed suit on Friday to declare the temporary, 90-day law unconstitutional. The class-action suit was filed on behalf of the parents of five teen-agers, a 12-year-old boy and three other individuals. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> criticized the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> suit last week, saying `` the <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> lawyers do n't sleep in these neighborhood where you ca n't sleep at night because gunshots, killings are going on.'' The curfew law requires persons under age 18 to be off the streets at 11 p.m. during the week, and by midnight on weekends. The curfew ends daily at 6 a.m.
