<HEAD>Brite &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DIXIE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The second million comes easy, the adage goes, but for <ORGANIZATION> Dixie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> students the problem is getting rid of the first million. The first million aluminum can pulltabs, that is. The tabs fill a large wooden bin on the second floor, spill down the stairways and litter the yard of the 1920s red brick schoolhouse in this town northeast of <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Walla </LOCATION>. The collection began 2 -LCB- years ago in <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Geddes </PERSON>' third - and fourth-grade classroom as a math project to learn the concept of a million `` You do n't often get the opportunity to see a million of anything,'' <PERSON> Geddes </PERSON> said. `` The kids love to look at them.'' Senior citizens, tavern owners, foreign students and a railroad sent the tabs in response to letters written by pupils. At a celebration Jan. 31, contributors wore buttons that read: `` I Helped Dixie Save A Million.'' The math lesson has expanded to geography and world affairs, said <PERSON> Geddes </PERSON>. Dixie pupils pinned tabs from <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> to a world map, and sent each contributor a hand-written thank you note. The school plans to donate the tabs to a charity _ at 50 cents a pound, the tabs would be worth about $ 600 _ but is having trouble finding the right one, said <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Yoder </PERSON>, the school superintendent. School officials were told the tabs could be traded for time on kidney dialysis machines, but found out later this was not true.
</TEXT>
