<HEAD>Army to Evaluate its Night-Vision Goggles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it will conduct a special one-time evaluation of every night-vision goggle in its inventory to ensure the devices are safe for use by aviators. The service, in a brief statement, said the evaluation would involve about 12,700 of the devices and would require at least two weeks and possibly more to complete. The evaluation will include not only the two models of night vision goggles that are being used now, but also two other models that were suspended from flight use a year ago when safety questions began arising. Critics have questioned whether the goggles function properly when used if there is no moon or in cloudy weather. According to recent published reports, 37 of 41 <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> helicopter crashes since 1978 in which night goggles were used occurred when there was not enough moonlight for the devices to amplify. The most recent incident in which the use of night vision goggles has been questioned occurred just a week ago on the night of March 12. A CH-3E helicopter assigned to the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> crashed near <LOCATION> Tucson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ariz. </LOCATION>, while ferrying some soldiers to a training range. Fifteen servicemen died in the accident. According to Capt. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Roque </PERSON>, a spokesman at the <ORGANIZATION> Davis-Monthan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>, where the helicopter was based, the crewmen on that chopper were wearing goggles that night. But investigators have determined the goggles were not a factor in the accident, <PERSON> Roque </PERSON> said. The evaluations will be conducted by experienced <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> pilots and will take about 20 minutes each, said Lt. Col. <PERSON> Greg </PERSON> <PERSON> Rixon </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. They can be performed on the ground in a specially lighted room. <PERSON> Rixon </PERSON> said the Army inspections are aimed at eliminating from the stockpile any goggles that suffer from a distortion problem that was identified some time ago. Inside the light-amplifying tubes of each goggle, there is a built-in twist to an optical fiber line that can produce distortion in the lens if not made properly, he explained. `` Every goggle that can be used for flight is going to be evaluated,'' <PERSON> Rixon </PERSON> said. `` If there are no problems, the goggle is cleared for use. If there is a problem, it takes about 45 minutes to change the tube.'' The spokesman said the cost of replacing the goggle tubes ranged from $ 1,100 to $ 5,000, depending upon the model.
</TEXT>
