<HEAD>Water Shortage Hits Okinawa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>'s worst water shortage in seven years has forced officials to cut water supplies throughout the southern Japanese prefecture for 24 hours every other day, officials said Monday. Water in two reservoirs averaged only 11.5 percent of capacity, while five reservoirs were averaging 44.6 percent of capacity, a local government official said. An <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> weather bureau official said only 0.78 inches of rain fell in the prefecture in February, or 17 percent of normal. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military spokesman <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodrigues </PERSON> declined to comment on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> armed forces radio reports saying all non-official travel by American troops to <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION> was suspended until further notice because of the water shortage. Of the 64,000 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> troops in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, about 35,000 are stationed in <LOCATION> Okinawa </LOCATION>, which has a population of 1.2 million. A water shortage in 1981-82 forced a similar 24-hour water supply cutoff for about six months.
