<FIRST>u a AM-DrunkenDriving Bjt   03-20 0634</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drunken Driving, Bjt,0648</SECOND>
<HEAD>Drunken Driving Drops When Drivers Estimate Blood Alcohol, Study
Suggests</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Wagenaar' in last graf is cq</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> town showed a markedly reduced drunken driving rate after residents were taught to use an inexpensive gadget to estimate their blood-alcohol levels, according to a study that experts called promising. The town's rate of driving with hazardous blood-alcohol levels was only about half that of a similar community that gave no training, the study found. Although the small study could provide only preliminary evidence that the program works, the results look encouraging, said co-author <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Worden </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vermont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION>. He and colleagues from the university and state government present the work in this month's issue of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>. Experts said the results were promising, but that some questions about effectiveness remain to be answered. They also said such a program should be considered only in combination with other strategies to reduce drunken driving. The study involved three <LOCATION> Vermont </LOCATION> communities which <PERSON> Worden </PERSON> declined to identify, two with populations of about 5,000 and the third approaching 12,000. They were similar in terms of education level, household income and the proportion of males among residents aged 16 to 29. In one community, an education program featured wallet-sized cards and small cardboard dials for estimating one's own blood-alcohol concentration according to body weight and the number of drinks consumed. About 3,000 dials were handed out in bars, stores, restaurants and filling stations. Customers were trained to use the dials at those outlets and in television announcements broadcast about 20 times a week. <PERSON> Worden </PERSON> stressed that training at the outlets was important because it ensured `` a lot of conversation about the program.'' A second town was exposed only to the television announcements, which mentioned a couple of local outlets for the dials. No training was provided at those outlets. The third town received no portion of the program. Six months after the program began, police stopped all traffic on six weekend nights in the three communities. Blood-alcohol concentrations were measured in 333 drivers from the community that had no part of the program, 405 from the town with only the television announcements, and 154 from the community with the full program. Analysis found that 11.1 percent of drivers from the town with no intervention had concentrations of at least 0.05 percent, the level at which the dial warned that driving becomes impaired. In the television-only community, 10.1 percent of drivers also reached that level. But only 5.8 percent of drivers from the full-program community scored that high. The legal driving limit of 0.1 percent blood alcohol was reached by 3 percent of drivers from the no-program community and 4.7 percent from the television-only community, but only 0.6 percent from the full-program community. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Graitcer </PERSON>, of the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>'s division of injury epidemiology and control, cautioned that questions remain about how effective such a program would be over a longer period, whether it would work in other settings, and whether it would in fact reduce accidents Still, the relatively inexpensive program offers `` a strategy that may work,'' he said. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mosher </PERSON>, program director at the <ORGANIZATION> Marin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prevention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alcohol </ORGANIZATION> and Other Drug Problems in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rafael </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, said the program would be best used in combination with other efforts, such as training bartenders and waiters to regulate drinking among patrons. Such a package of strategies could also include increasing the excise tax on alcoholic beverages and using local laws to decrease risk of drunken driving, said <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagenaar </PERSON>, head of the injury analysis and prevention group at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Arbor </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
