<SECOND>AM-China, Bjt,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Li Peng Opens Congress on Somber Note Stressing Economic Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> opened the annual legislative session Monday with a somber speech on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economic crisis that stressed centralized control and the need to halt political reforms. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s senior leader, 84-year-old <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>, did not attend the session of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> as he did last year. A Foreign Affairs Ministry official said only that <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> `` asked for leave.'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s speech to the 2,768 legislators in the cavernous Great Hall of the People marked the consolidation of a policy of economic and political retrenchment that began in September. Whereas <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last year called for democracy and bold attempts to free <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy from rigid central planning, <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s speech called for control. `` Experience has proved time and again that without the necessary centralization and unity, without strict organization and discipline, it would be absolutely impossible to readjust the economy and overcome difficulties,'' he said. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> also appeared to level veiled but pointed criticism at <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, who as premier in 1987 launched <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> on an ambitious reform program. Silent for most of the 130-minute speech, the delegates erupted in applause six times near its end when <PERSON> Li </PERSON> turned from the troubled economy to issues at the heart of Chinese nationalism: <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and foreign affairs. Any support for the independence of <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said in reference to recent bloody riots in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>, `` constitutes an outrageous interference in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s internal affairs and will absolutely not be tolerated.'' He also warned the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to `` refrain from interfering with <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s internal affairs ... lest the existing friendly relations between the two countries be impaired.'' The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> have expressed concern over the violent suppression of <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> riots in which at least 16 people were killed this month. Most of the speech, however, focused on <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s troubled domestic situation. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> read slowly, in a low monotone, pausing often to clear his throat. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> faces a record 36 percent inflation that has sparked panic buying and bank runs. Rising crime affects its cities and corruption sullies the halls of government. Much of the troubles have been blamed on inflation. In September, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> began a program to tackle price rises by slowing reforms designed to introduce elements of a market economy to the state-run system. `` Both government and people should be mentally prepared for a few years of austerity,'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> warned. Price reform, construction projects, loans, industrial growth and consumer demand all should be cut, he said. Even some productive projects `` should be stopped or suspended'' and necessary construction projects `` follow an order of importance and urgency.'' Only education and agriculture would be spared, <PERSON> Li </PERSON> said. To halt a four-year slide in grain production, the state will raise its grain purchase price by 18 percent on April 1, he said. And banks will increase agricultural loans. He also announced a 15 percent increase in the education budget, to $ 10 billion. Both sectors are considered key to development and critics say they have been overlooked in recent budgets. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> appeared to blame party leader <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> for inflation _ the root of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s trouble. <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> backed a full-steam-ahead approach to reforms when he was premier in 1987, while <PERSON> Li </PERSON> was more cautious. At one point, <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> said the only criterion for whether reforms were successful was whether they raised production. <PERSON> Li </PERSON>'s speech roundly criticized this. `` We were too optimistic in our assessment of the economic situation in 1987,'' he said. `` Instead of taking effective measures ... we relaxed control over and readjusted the prices of more commodities only to intensify the panic of the masses over the price hikes and evoke a buying spree.'' The premier ignored a growing public clamor among intellectuals for greater freedom of speech, evidenced by a recent call for an amnesty for political prisoners. Instead, he said, all dialogue must take place `` under the leadership of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.'' <PERSON> Li </PERSON> also said the economic troubles made it necessary to postpone temporarily political reforms that would give more decision-making power to businesses previously run by the state. Also, overstaffed governments were to be cut back and a civil service system introduced. The congress is meeting through April 4. Two important laws are expected to pass. One will give citizens the right to sue the government. The other outlines the powers of the congress, which does little but routinely endorse policy directed by the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
