<HEAD>Astronaut Wanted To Take Space Walk, Mom Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Astronaut <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> had hoped something might go wrong on the five-day voyage of Discovery so he could leave the space shuttle to fix it, his mother says. `` Bob was hoping for just some little problem so he could take a space walk,'' <PERSON> Betty </PERSON> <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> said Sunday from her son's home in <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. Instead, the flight was almost perfect, which suited Mrs. Spring fine. The only problem concerned an erratic pressure reading from a hydrogen tank that helps supply electricity to the orbiter. The astronauts conserved electricity for a day until ground controllers corrected the difficulty. Mrs. <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, watched the shuttle take off in <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canaveral </LOCATION>, then went to <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> and watched on TV the landing Saturday. <PERSON> Springer </PERSON>, a 46-year-old mission specialist aboard the shuttle, returned to his home in the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> suburbs after the landing. `` It still seems like a dream, but he really liked his trip up into space,'' his mother said. <PERSON> Springer </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> Ashland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, where his parents still live.
