<HEAD>Commerce Department Says China Dumps Imports of Headwear</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Monday it has made a final determination that hats, caps and visors from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are being sold in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> at less than fair-market value. As a result of the finding, cash deposits or bonds will be imposed on the imported headwear, which include items made from certain natural and man-made fibers but not hats made of straw, felt or wool. If the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> finds that the low-priced imports harm <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry, <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> will instruct the <ORGANIZATION> Customs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to collect the final anti-dumping duties. The <ORGANIZATION> ITC </ORGANIZATION> has 45 days to make a ruling. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> began its investigation after the <ORGANIZATION> Headwear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> filed a petition on behalf of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> industry. Imports of headwear from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1987 were valued at about $ 40 million.
