<HEAD>Pan Am Dispute Produces Classic British Political Confrontation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Flight 103, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At the center of the controversy over bomb warnings before the <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> Flight 103 disaster is a classic British political confrontation: an old Etonian millionaire Cabinet minister vs. an ex-waiter leading an opposition onslaught. For Transport Secretary <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Channon </PERSON>, son of a British brewing heiress and an American social high-flyer, the Dec. 21 crash in <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> was the low point in an unprecedented string of rail, air and sea disasters in the past two years. And from his departure for a vacation at his private villa in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> on Dec. 23 through mounting charges the past five days that he bungled bomb warnings, <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> has been under concerted attack by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON>, a railman's son who is the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s transport spokesman. `` My response is one of contempt,'' <PERSON> Channon </PERSON> said over the weekend. `` His behavior has been both callous and cynical. ... He is exploiting the grief of the bereaved.'' The latest furor began after a newspaper revealed last week that <PERSON> Channon </PERSON>'s department warned British airlines Nov. 22 of a radio-cassette bomb, four days after the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> sent the same warning to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines, including <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>. A detailed description and picture of the bomb dated Dec. 19 was mailed `` in the new year'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to British airlines and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines _ well after a bomb hidden in a radio-cassette player brought down Flight 103 over the Scottish v