<FIRST>r w AM-MedicineCaps     03-20 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Medicine Caps,350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Child-Proof, but not Elderly-Proof, Cap Demonstrated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Poison specialists on Monday demonstrated a new child-resistant medicine cap they hope will solve the problem of caps that are too difficult for the elderly to open. In ceremonies marking the opening of National Poison Prevention Week, <PERSON> Anne </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>, the acting chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, noted that roughly half the accidental medical poisonings of children under age 5 were from child-resistant packages that had not been properly resecured or from non-child resistance containers holding medicines originally packed in child-resistant containers. Child poisonings have declined greatly with the advent of the child-resistant caps, from 216 deaths of children under 5 in 1972 to 59 in 1986. Nonethess, Ms. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> noted, studies show that 35 percent of the medicines ingested in child-poisoning cases come from people not in the immediate family, most frequently grandparents. Like the present mechanism, the new cap device has an inner and outer cap that lock together when the outer cap is pressed down on the inner cap. Unlike the present design, the inner and outer caps of the new mechanism each has a small slot across part of a diameter. When the slots are aligned, a spoon handle may be inserted into both to make the two caps turn together, using the spoon as a lever, without downward pressure on the outer cap. `` This is our first effort,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wygant </PERSON>, professor of industrial engineering at <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kalamazoo </LOCATION>, at the news conference at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capital </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>. `` We have many other tests to do.'' <PERSON> Wygant </PERSON> developed the prototype cap from a design by Professor <PERSON> Hugh </PERSON> <PERSON> Lockhart </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. The design emerged from earlier work by <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Wygant </PERSON>, who estimated that more than a billion caps are made for medicine alone every year, said that among other problems to be solved was the production of clear instructions and making the caps easy to manufacture. Commission spokesmen said the commission plans to require use of the caps, or something similar, once all the bugs are worked out.
