<FIRST>r i AM-Chernobyl     03-20 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chernobyl,0757</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Living on Radiation-Contaminated Land</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Almost a quarter-million Soviets are living on land so contaminated by the <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> disaster that they must receive special food supplies to avoid overexposure to radiation, the newspaper Pravda said Monday. The Communist Party daily printed maps showing contaminated areas of <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> and the Russian republic in response to readers' complaints they still did n't have full information about the level of contamination nearly three years after the accident. It was accompanied by a commentary by Pravda science editor <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gubarev </PERSON>, who criticized officials for trying to duck public concern about the safety of nuclear power. `` Yes, it is impossible to get around using nuclear power stations. However, why then are they proposed for heavily populated or seismic zones?'' <PERSON> Gubarev </PERSON> asked. `` Why is the quality of construction so low, and why does so much defective equipment arrive at nuclear plants? And, finally, what is the source of this fear before a public which rightly demands a wide debate of every proposed nuclear power station?'' <PERSON> Yuri </PERSON> <PERSON> Izrael </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hydrometeorology </ORGANIZATION>, said with decontamination efforts and food brought into the area, those on the lands contaminated by Cesium 137 can live safely without exceeding radiation limits set by the government. Soviet officials began bringing food supplies into areas surrounding the Chernobyl plant shortly after the accident, but they had not previously said how many people were living in those areas. The publication came as Soviet officials again started to move villagers who have continued to live in areas surrounding the plant since the accident in April 1986 that killed at least 31 people. In February, scientists decided that 20 Byelorussian villages must be evacuated because over a lifetime their residents would receive an unacceptably high dose of radiation. Earlier this month, officials announced that five villages in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> also would be evacuated. In November, the Soviet government set a maxium lifetime dose of 35 rem -LRB- roetgen equivalent, man -RRB- for exposure to radiation. That figure has a comfortable margin of safety built into it, <PERSON> Izrael </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Izrael </PERSON> said the area of the three republics where the current level of radiation from both the environment and existing food supplies would expose residents to more than 35 rem includes 4,000 square miles including about 640 settlements with 230,000 people. That includes 800 square miles in the Russian republic, 600 square miles in the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> and 2,800 square miles in <LOCATION> Byelorussia </LOCATION>, including 1,200 square miles in areas that have been evacuated. `` So far they have gone the route here of trying to guarantee this population clean food and extra income,'' <PERSON> Izrael </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Izrael </PERSON> said studies showed that residents could remain safely as long as they did not eat the food, especially meat and milk produced in the area, which sharply increased the amount of radiation to which they were exposed. He quoted the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Byelorussia </ORGANIZATION> as saying in a study of the <LOCATION> Gomel </LOCATION>, Mogilev and <LOCATION> Brest </LOCATION> regions of the republic less than 0.1 percent of the population had received an unacceptably high level of radiation. As of last fall, there had been no cases of radiation sickness, he said. Scientists are debating how many more cancer deaths might be expected in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> as a result of the Chernobyl accident. In <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, they have estimated there may be up to 200,000 deaths in the next 20 to 25 years from <LOCATION> Chernobyl </LOCATION> radiation. But <PERSON> Izrael </PERSON> said that long years of work were ahead to decontaminate the region. `` Insufficiencies in this work must be compensated by replacement with clean food -LRB- especially by bringing in milk -RRB-. In this case life and work is possible within the framework of the acceptable levels established by the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Izrael </PERSON> said that within the first days after the explosion and fire at the Chernobyl plant's No. 4 reactor, the direction of the wind made a complete circle and dropped radiation all around the plant. The entire population living within 18 -LCB- miles of the plant, or about 135,000 people, were evacuated and resettled. Since then, many Soviets have begun to speak out against nuclear power. Citizens' protests or tougher standards imposed after the Chernobyl accident have stopped several nuclear power plants. A plant near <LOCATION> Yerevan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION>, not far from the site of the Dec. 7 earthquake, was shut down Saturday.
