<HEAD>Charges Reconsidered In Boston Police Misconduct Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Detectives whose partner was killed during a drug raid lied so many times to try to bring the alleged murderer to trial that they blew the case, defense lawyers argued Monday. Other lawyers say the admitted misconduct by police could also call into question dozens of convictions in which the officers participated. Defense attorneys and the prosecutor agreed during the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> hearing Monday that there was serious police misconduct in the case against <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>, 33, accused of shooting the detective Feb. 17, 1987. But the prosecutor, Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Meara </PERSON>, argued that <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> should stand trial because there is strong evidence against him and because the police have `` come clean'' by admitting they lied to obtain a search warrant and hid the identity of potential witnesses. The three detectives, <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Luna </PERSON>, 32, <PERSON> Hugo </PERSON> <PERSON> Amate </PERSON>, 31, and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schroeder </PERSON>, 33, were suspended with pay while the attorney general investigates possible perjury. Judge <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grabau </PERSON> dismissed the murder charge against <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> last month, but agreed to consider reinstating it after the detectives filed affidavits last week admitting they previously lied. <PERSON> Grabau </PERSON> said he would rule next week whether <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> can be tried for the murder of Detective <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> <PERSON> Griffiths </PERSON>. Defense attorney <PERSON> Max </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON> argued that the case against <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON> is weak and depends heavily on testimony from other potential suspects who may be lying to protect themselves. <PERSON> Griffiths </PERSON>, 36, was kill