<SECOND>AM-UN-Toxic Waste,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Toxic Waste Treaty-Signing Conference Opens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BASEL, Switzerland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Diplomats and ministers from 111 nations met Monday for a U.N.-sponsored toxic waste conference to culminate in a treaty regulating international trafficking of dangerous products. But African delegations demanded alterations in the 51-page draft document and threatened to stall the three-day meeting. If approved, the treaty formally gives all signing countries the right to refuse imports of hazardous wastes and requires exporters to provide prospective recipients details of shipments. Signatories will pledge to dispose of dangerous waste in an environmentally sound way and also will commit to keep international toxic waste traffic to a minimum. <PERSON> Mostafa </PERSON> <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Program </ORGANIZATION>, said international hazardous waste trade is threatening public health and the environment. At least 100,000 shipments of toxic waste crosses international borders annually in a `` commerce of poison'' worth billions of dollars, <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON> told delegates at the opening session. <PERSON> Tolba </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Basel </LOCATION> treaty would signal the end of uncontrolled hazardous waste transport. But <LOCATION> Mali </LOCATION>'s environment minister, <PERSON> Morifing </PERSON> <PERSON> Kone </PERSON>, speaking for the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unity </ORGANIZATION>, said the treaty contains gaps. He said some African nations want a guarantee that industrialized countries wo n't use developing areas as a dumping ground for poisonous wastes. <ORGANIZATION> Greenpeace </ORGANIZATION>, the international environmental group, on Monday criticized the treaty for not covering radioactive waste and allowing member countries to sign waste trade pacts with non-member nations. The problem of international trafficking in dangerous wastes was dramatized last year when several waste shipments from industrialized countries were found dumped in African nations, including <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guinea </LOCATION>. Waste-laden ships traveled from port to port looking for a place to dispose of their cargo. Environmentalists said they were concerned that importing toxic waste had become a source of income for poor countries with no safe disposal plans. <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s attention was drawn to the problem earlier when barrels of toxic waste from <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Seveso </LOCATION> chemical plant spill vanished in 1982 before turning up months later in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. The incident led to the adoption of European Community rules on cross-border dangerous waste transport.
