<HEAD>Gunmen Kill 17 Sinhalese, Indian Troops Shoot 12 Tamils</HEAD>
<BYLINE>BY DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Gunmen killed 17 Sinhalese men in a shooting spree in north-central <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lanka </LOCATION>, and Indian troops shot and killed 12 Tamil rebels in separate weekend clashes, witnesses and the military said Monday. Residents of Tirappane village said on condition of anonymity that the Sinhalese victims were shot and then hacked to death Sunday by unidentified assailants. Also on Sunday, Sinhalese rebels were blamed for seven other deaths, military officials said. The motive behind the Tirappane killings was not immediately known, but residents said the murders may be linked to the assassination of three policemen by Sinhalese radicals in a nearby village earlier Sunday. The policemen were killed when Sinhalese rebels detonated explosives by remote control and blew up a jeep at <LOCATION> Epawalla </LOCATION> <LOCATION> village </LOCATION>, about 15 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Anuradhapura </LOCATION> town. Police said an organization known as the `` Black Cats'' may be responsible for the Tirappane murders. The group's aim is to eliminate supporters of the radical Sinhalese group known as the <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, police said. The Sinhalese Front is opposed to the government's peace offers to Tamil rebels. Sinhalese radicals also killed four people on Sunday in <LOCATION> Kaduwela </LOCATION>, a <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION> suburb. Elsewhere, six Tamil rebels were killed when they tried to ambush an Indian patrol in northern <LOCATION> Jaffna </LOCATION>, 185 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. Six more rebels were killed in a second clash with <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> soldiers in <LOCATION> Mullaitivu </LOCATION> district, about 170 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Colombo </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> has an estimated 40,000 troops in <LOCATION> Sri </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lan