<BYLINE>By ELOY O. AGUILAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> used his own commercial success and public discontent with a long civil war to overcome his party's image of an ultra-right movement linked to death squads. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, who claimed victory in Sunday's presidential election, says his <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> party, known as <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, is a political force no one can ignore. Arena was founded by <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>, a former army major frequently accused of organizing right-wing death squads, and many people wonder whether <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> runs the party or is a figurehead for d'Aubuisson. Before the election, <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government `` can not dismiss'' his party `` in the simplistic manner it did in the past.'' `` We consider the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> our natural ally, but it can not come and impose models or conditions,'' said <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, who attended <ORGANIZATION> Georgetown </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administrations have criticized <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>, who was dismissed from the army in 1980 on grounds of plotting a coup. The party founder denies the allegations against him. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> formed the party in 1981. It has gained popularity in recent years and it won a slim legislative majority in 1988, which puts it in the position of controlling both the legislative and executive branches. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, a 41-year-old coffee farmer and distributor of medical supplies, appealed in the campaign to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>'s traditionally conservative middle and upper classes, and to others tired of a 9-year-old war that has taken more than 70,000 lives. `` I'd rather be sitting in my office'' than running for president,'' he said in a pre-election interview. `` I am here because I am convinced that my country can progress if we are free in every sense of the word and adopt an economic model for development.'' At his side throughout the campaign was d'Aubuisson, stirring up the crowds at rallies. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> lost the 1984 presidential election to <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Democrat </PERSON> <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, a member of Arena since 1982, became the party president in 1985 when <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON> stopped down from that post. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> is currently an Arena representative in the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> and is still referred to by many party members as `` maximum leader.'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, who has not been linked to the death squads, was elected to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> in 1985 and re-elected last year. In a recent interview by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Christiani </PERSON> was asked why <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON> had quit as <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> president. `` He recognized that his figure and all that had been said about him was prejudicial to the party's image,'' he said. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> also commented on the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and d'Aubuisson. `` <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> personally can not expect the support of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' he said. `` Even if he were to be born again his image could not be changed there. They damaged it so much beyond salvation.'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> blames <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>'s image problem on the foreign news media _ especially the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> media. He also has criticized the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government for what he calls the `` distortion'' of <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>'s image. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> is a tall, angular man with a soft voice, graying moustache and hair combed straight back, an exemplar of the economic class that blames the military and politicians of the past for the nation's ills. `` We may be conservative,'' he said of <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, `` but we are the only party that has defined the social problems of the country and that offers a solution.'' He said President <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, barred by the consitution from seeking re-election, failed to end the war and solve economic problems. `` We must have a clear economic model _ a free market _ that benefits all sectors of society; avoid protectionism, -LRB- and -RRB- let the government take care only of those services where private business will not enter,'' he said. Peace is a `` viable probablity'' if leftist guerrillas join the democratic process, he said. If they do n't, the alternative is `` efficient, professional use of the armed forces, but we would rather sit down and talk about a national peace proposal so we all may re-enter a peaceful life,'' <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> declared. `` Some objectives have been achieved and the main thing is that all political parties are participating in the election.'' <PERSON> Ana </PERSON> <PERSON> Guadalupe </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, a member of the rebel political commission, said in an interview in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> that <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> is on the `` rational'' right but she fears <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON> is `` the power behind the throne.''
