<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The payment of monthly `` imminent danger'' bonuses to sailors deployed in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> will come to an end April 1, the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. The bonuses, previously known as hostile fire or combat pay, are worth $ 110 a month and have been paid to servicemen working inside the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> since August 25, 1987. Defense sources disclosed almost two months ago that Gen. <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Schwarzkopf </PERSON>, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Command </ORGANIZATION>, had recommended an end to the bonuses because the truce in the Iran-Iraq war was continuing to hold. Adm. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chiefs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Staff </ORGANIZATION>, approved the recommendation recently and officials in the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s manpower office then signed the order Monday, said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. According to <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> statistics, about $ 16 million has been paid out in danger bonuses since August 1987. Before the ceasefire took hold in the Iran-Iraq war last August, about 8,000 servicemen were receiving the payments every month. While most of those receiving the bonuses were deployed on ships in the region or flew warplanes over the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>'s waters, servicemen assigned to small bases in <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> were also eligible. As a result, about 1,300 women also received the bonuses at one point or