<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumAlternative     03-20 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Alternative,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Urges Accelerator Development as Reactor Alternative</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Use of a linear accelerator to produce tritium for nuclear weapons appears to be a promising alternative to current <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plans to build new production reactors, according to a scientific report released Monday. The report, prepared by scientists at the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alamos </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Brookhaven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, national laboratories, urged consideration of an accelerator as a possible backup to building new reactors at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> complex in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Idaho </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Engineering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>. The report said construction of new reactors was the `` lowest technical risk approach to supplying the critical need for tritium.'' `` However, we believe it is prudent that DOE pursue other technologies for tritium production to provide potential alternatives as a contingency for the future,'' the report said. `` One concept that appears to be particularly promising is the accelerator production of tritium.'' <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON>, acting head of the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reactors </ORGANIZATION>, told a special panel of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Monday that the department has yet to see the report. `` We will review the report with great interest,'' <PERSON> Cochran </PERSON> said, adding that department believes the accelerator proposal involves a `` level of risk too great at this time'' to make it an alternative to constructing the reactors. The nation's current supply of tritium is threatened by the crumbling conditions at the department's existing production reactors and weapons plants. An accelerator is essentially a long tunnel in which subatomic particles are whipped at high speed until they crash into a target, in this case lithium clad in aluminum. The resulting collision produces tritium _ a critical element in nuclear weapons that increases the power of warheads, but decays rapidly. The report said that an accelerator could be completed within eight to nine years on an aggressive schedule compared with at least 10 years to finish a new production reactor. An accelerator would cost about $ 2.3 billion, including $ 600 million for contingencies, the report said. The estimated cost of the new <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> reactor has been pegged at about $ 3.2 billion, while the <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> reactor would cost about $ 3.6 billion.
</TEXT>
