<HEAD>Pan Am Warned of Security Gaps in 1986, Congresswoman Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with fresh reaction, subbing 10th graf, Jeffrey Kriendler</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airways </ORGANIZATION> has yet to implement many steps recommended by a security consultant who in 1986 warned that the airline was doing little to prevent bombs from being smuggled onto aircraft, a congresswoman said Monday. According to Rep. <PERSON> Cardiss </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, D-Ill., the Israeli security firm <ORGANIZATION> KPI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> cautioned the carrier more than two years ago that it was `` highly vulnerable'' to terrorist attacks `` The fact that no major disaster has occurred to date is merely providential,'' <ORGANIZATION> KPI </ORGANIZATION> wrote in September 1986, Mrs. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. Last Dec. 21, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s Flight 103 was blown from the skies over <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> by a bomb authorities say was placed in a radio-cassette player, killing 270 people. Mrs. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, chairwoman of the <ORGANIZATION> Goverment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Operations </ORGANIZATION> transportation subcommittee, wrote a letter to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> on Monday quoting portions of reports the security company wrote to <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> in September and November of 1986. Mrs. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> wrote that `` within days'' of the completion of the September 1986 paper, a terrorist attack in <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, killed 18 <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> passengers and crew members. The studies included examinations of security at nine airports, including <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Heathrow </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Flight 103 originated in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and had landed in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. Mrs. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>' letter said that according to information her panel has gathered `` from a variety of sources,'' <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> has yet to correct `` many of the gaps'' specified in the 1986 studies. `` If they had been, it is possible that those lives could have been saved,'' she wrote, referring to the <LOCATION> Scotland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> disasters. <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Kriendler </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s corporate communications vice president at the airline's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> headquarters, said <ORGANIZATION> KPI </ORGANIZATION> is unfamiliar with <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION>'s current security program. He said the company would not respond to <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>' criticism until corporate officials had seen the letter. The <ORGANIZATION> KPI </ORGANIZATION> reports concluded that <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> conducted insufficient checks of baggage, did a poor job of questioning passengers boarding planes, and was slow to react to warnings of possible terrorist activity, according to Mrs. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>. `` In conclusion, there are no adequate safeguards under the presently operating security system that would prevent a passenger from boarding a plane with explosives on his person or in his baggage, whether or not he is aware of the fact,'' the security company wrote. The reports said X-ray examinations of luggage should be replaced with manual searches, which were performed too infrequently. `` On the whole, the presently employed search techniques stand a low chance of discovering concealed explosive charges, if at all,'' the consultant wrote. The company wrote that careful scrutiny of lost-and-found baggage `` is very rare,'' making it simple for explosives `` to be sent ownerless to a supposed destination.'' At some airports, including <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, baggage with a <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> tag simply placed on a conveyer belt would be loaded onto planes, even without a registered passenger, <ORGANIZATION> KPI </ORGANIZATION> said. The consultant criticized airline employees for being too lax when searching the baggage of Americans and of citizens of each airport's country, considering them safer. `` It might be pointed out that the question of citizenship is irrelevant to the terrorist threat,'' <ORGANIZATION> KPI </ORGANIZATION> said. The consultant said it found little effort to carefully scrutinize suspicious-looking passengers. It also complained that in some instances, warnings of terrorist plans were not relayed to all <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> security workers. In one incident, all <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> security employees at <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> were not told of a warning received about two <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> women who were planning to place explosives aboard a plane. The report did not say what the consequences were.
