<HEAD>Michelangelo Would Have Run Afoul of Schlock Art Law, Attorney Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michelangelo </PERSON> would have run afoul of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> law if he tried to sell his painting of the <ORGANIZATION> Sistine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chapel </ORGANIZATION> as an original, an attorney challenging the state's new `` schlock art'' law claimed Monday. `` The statute as it is written defines ` original' as requiring only one person to work on it, and <PERSON> Michelangelo </PERSON> had apprentices that helped him out,'' said attorney <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Nathanson </PERSON>. <PERSON> Nathanson </PERSON> represents <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paintings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which sells oil paintings for $ 35 to $ 200 in seaside art galleries and shopping malls up and down the Eastern seaboard. The company sued <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> saying the state law _ the first of its sort in the nation _ is vague and unconstitutional. The law bans the sale of `` non-original art'' unless it is labeled `` not an original.'' It defines original as `` independently created and executed and signed by the individual artist'' _ a standard <PERSON> Nathanson </PERSON> insists many Old Masters could not meet. After a three-day trial last week, both sides are now waiting for <ORGANIZATION> Suffolk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Cratsley </PERSON> to decide what separates original art from schlock. <PERSON> Cratsley </PERSON> is not expected to rule until next month at the earliest. The state legislator who wrote the law said he only intended to keep consumers from being sold cheap copies under the guise of `` original'' art. State Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Buell </PERSON> said `` schlock art'' companies put names similar to those of famous artists on paintings that are very similar to the well-known works. While such paintings stop short of forgery, <PERSON> Buell </PERSON> said, they are certainly not original. `` There's nothing wrong with selling it,'' said <PERSON> Buell </PERSON>, who sponsored the law on behalf of artists in the seaside resort of <LOCATION> Rockport </LOCATION>. `` It's just deceitful to tell the customer who's paying $ 45 or $ 65 that he's getting an original painting.'' <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION>, in a broad attack on the law, has asked the court not only to define original but also to explain how police officers charged with enforcing the law could be expected to make such distinctions. <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON>, the assistant attorney general defending the state, has argued that the point is moot since <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> has never been prosecuted, though it has sold more than 60,000 paintings since the law was passed. <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> also has argued that the law is constitutional because it protects consumers against deceptive marketing. He told the judge it could be used to prosecute those who copy others' work, make machine reproductions and sell them as original oil paintings or sign false names to paintings. <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> dismissed the <PERSON> Michelangelo </PERSON> example, saying any law could be challenged in the abstract using far-fetched examples. `` How are they going to sell the <ORGANIZATION> Sistine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chapel </ORGANIZATION>, anyway?'' he said. `` Is it like selling the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION>?''
