<HEAD>Police Say Bloody Underworld War Has Ended</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The boss of a gang battling <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s top underworld syndicate told police his gang will disband, ending the bloodiest gangster vendetta in postwar Japanese history, police said Monday. <PERSON> Hiroshi </PERSON> <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON>, 64, visited a police station near his home Sunday afternoon to announce his decision to disband the Ichiwa-kai gang, said police in <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION>, a major port city in western <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. `` He came here, told us the gang was disbanding, and left. It all took about three minutes,'' the officer at Higashi-Nada precinct said. It is not uncommon for gangsters to make such appearances at police stations, and many bosses even make written vows to police to end conflicts or disband gangs, said the officer, who spoke on condition of anonymity. But he said police are still waiting for a reaction from the rival Yamaguchi-gumi, by far the nation's largest crime syndicate, and further skirmishes could erupt. The Ichiwa-kai, which had an estimated 6,000 members at its peak, was created in June 1984 after an internal dispute over <ORGANIZATION> Yamaguchi-gumi </ORGANIZATION>'s leadership led to a revolt by followers of boss-candidate <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON>. In January 1985, two Ichiwa-kai gangsters fatally shot Yamaguchi-gumi boss <PERSON> Masahisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Takenaka </PERSON> and two other syndicate leaders. The <ORGANIZATION> Osaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday upheld a lower court verdict sentencing the two to life imprisonment and also upheld sentences of 10 years for three Ichiwa-kai lookouts. The Ichiwa-kai attack left the Yamaguchi-gumi without a leader, although acting boss <PERSON> Kazuo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nakanishi </PERSON> and `` young leader'' <PERSON> Yoshinori </PERSON> <PERSON> Watanabe </PERSON> quickly led the gang into the bloody vendetta, known to the Japanese as the `` Yama-Ichi War.'' Police say 315 armed incidents during the four-year battle between the two gangs left 25 people dead and more than 70 injured. A Yamaguchi-gumi source said <PERSON> Yamamoto </PERSON> `` timed the breakup of the gang to match the sentencing, as a kind of gesture to the Yamaguchi-gumi.'' He spoke on condition of anonymity. In <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, where gun laws are strict and violent crime rates low, the high-profile gunfights created public outrage and spawned grassroots movements to rid residential areas of gang headquarters and offices. The strongest of those movements evicted a <LOCATION> Yamaguchi-gumi </LOCATION> affiliate from a residential area in <LOCATION> Hamamatsu </LOCATION>, central <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, and the gang today is on the verge of disbanding. Headquarters of both the Yamaguchi-gumi and the Ichiwa-kai are in expensive residential districts in <LOCATION> Kobe </LOCATION>, but their presence has not faced serious local opposition. When the Ichiwa-kai split from the Yamaguchi-gumi, the organization had roughly 10,000 members. Police say it now has more than 20,000. Police say about 86,000 gangsters operate in 3,200 gangs in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Nearly 40 percent belong to the big three nationwide syndicates: the Yamaguchi-gumi, Sumiyoshi Rengo-kai and <LOCATION> Inagawa-kai </LOCATION>. The latter two are based in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>.
