l talk to the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> considers the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> a terrorist group, and a succession of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> governments has vowed never to negotiate with it. <PERSON> Weizman </PERSON>, a leading member of the left-leaning Labor party, reiterated his well-known position that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> should negotiate with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> and predicted that talks could begin within two years. Monday's third main participant, <PERSON> Mustafa </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalil </PERSON>, was a senior aide to the late President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>, whose 1977 trip to <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> led to peace between the two countries. Despite diplomatic relations, <LOCATION> Egyptian-Israeli </LOCATION> cooperation in most fields has been very limited. Large numbers of Israeli tourists come to <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>, but few Egyptians go to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Several Egyptian participants at Monday's session indicated the extent to which bad blood remains from four <LOCATION> Arab-Israeli </LOCATION> wars since 1948. <PERSON> Khaled </PERSON> <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON>, a student at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>, said he had come to the session to discuss <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, but `` I did not know there would be Israelis here before I came. If I had known, personally, I would not have come.''
