<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The army on Monday barred journalists from the border region where Nicaraguan rebel camps are located after two soldiers were killed by mines in the area. The soldiers were patrolling on foot near the town of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Congolona </LOCATION>, 100 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>, when they stepped on the mines Thursday, according to armed forces spokesman Col. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Benavides </PERSON>. Military teams worked over the weekend to clear mines from a 20-square-mile area at the border, he said. `` The Sandinista army has intensified the mining of different Honduran border zones with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> by making rapid incursions into our territory with what appears to be an attitude of provocation,'' <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> <PERSON> Benavides </PERSON> said. `` To avoid acts that we would later regret, the decision was made not to permit journalists to enter Yamales.'' The area is along the <LOCATION> Yamales </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>, 102 miles east of <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>; the road to <LOCATION> Yamales </LOCATION> runs to within 200 yards of the border with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in some places. Contra rebels, who have operated from camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> since 1981, also are known have planted mines when retreating across the border. Nicaraguan officials had no immediate comment. The two countries regularly exchange accusations on border incidents. Also Monday, <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Eugenio </PERSON> <PERSON> Castro </PERSON> <PERSON> Claramount </PERSON> said at least 14 Hondurans are among the 1,894 former Nicaraguan national guardsmen released last week in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. He said they will soon be returning to <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>. The Nicaraguan army reported 20 incidents of harassment from Honduran troops across the border from <LOCATION> Teotecacinte </LOCATION>, near the <LOCATION> Yamales </LOCATION> area, this year. No casualties were reported. About 11,000 Contra rebels and their families retreated to base camps in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> after the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> cut off military aid about a year ago. They have been receiving food, medical supplies and other non-lethal <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid. For many years access to the camps was strictly restricted by the Honduran government, but foreign journalists have been able to visit the camps frequently in recent months, usually traveling there by road from <LOCATION> Tegucigalpa </LOCATION>.
