<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 It might have been a warning or a prank, but the `` gift'' someone left for reputed mobster <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotti </PERSON> in front of his Little <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> hangout on Monday was not a workable bomb, police said. When bomb squad officers opened a plastic box they found on the step of the <ORGANIZATION> Ravenite </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, they at first described what they found inside as an explosive powder. But further analysis disclosed the powder to be two pounds of salt and an ounce of gunpowder. Given such a small amount of powder, plus faulty batteries and wiring, `` it appears the device would not have detonated,'' Chief of Detectives <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Colangelo </PERSON> told reporters. If it had, he added, it probably could n't have done much damage. Asked to explain the incident, he said: `` We could assume it's either a message to <PERSON> Gotti </PERSON> that perhaps he is vulnerable or that his club is vulnerable It could have been a prank. It could have been a lot of things.'' A man telephoned the police department's organized crime bureau shortly after 5 a.m. and said, `` There is a gift for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gotti </PERSON> at the social club.'' He did not give his name, but identified the club as the Ravenite in lower <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. Police Inspector <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayronne </PERSON> said the device included a 10-inch aluminum bottle packed with powder. The bottle was partially contained in a 4-by-6 inch plastic box which contained batteries wired to a circuit board with an electric timer. The bottle, which contained the powder and a coil, protruded from inside the box. The non-bomb was the latest slap at <PERSON> Gotti </PERSON>, reputed boss of the Gambino crime family, who is besieged by law enforcers and mob rivals. In January a battalion of police officers, some of them posing