<HEAD>Right-Winger Cristiani Victorious in Salvador Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to CORRECT name of U.S. ambassador and move
up his comment. Pick up 16th pvs, `Cristiani, a...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, who tried to erase memories of his right-wing party's links to death squads that killed thousands of Salvadorans, celebrated his presidential victory Monday over the U.S.-backed government. <PERSON> Fidel </PERSON> <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON>, candidate of the incumbent <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>, conceded defeat and told a news conference, `` I have called him -LRB- <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> -RRB- personally to congratulate him and express my desire that God illuminate him in governing the country.'' <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Ambassador <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> said the election result was not a defeat for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said it was prepared to support the new Salvadoran government but only if it protects democracy and human rights. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, or <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, will take over from President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> on June 1. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s staunchest allies, had been unable to end a 9-year-old civil war with leftist rebels that has taken an estimated 70,000 lives. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON>, barred by the constitution from seeking re-election, has said his proudest moment will come when he hands over power to an elected successor. <PERSON> Duarte </PERSON> suffers from terminal liver cancer. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> immediately urged all political parties to `` put down their political banners and unite to ensure progress.'' He told a Monday news conference that his party `` does n't want a sectarian government.'' He also thanked <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON> for accepting `` in a very democratic manner the results of the elections.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elections </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> had 53.81 percent of the 576,339 votes counted from Sunday's election, compared to 36.59 percent for the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION>. Trailing were the conservative <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conciliation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> with 4.21 percent and the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convergence </ORGANIZATION> at 3.2 percent. Other votes were divided among three smaller parties. `` Arena has won and I congratulate <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> publicly,'' said <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Perdomo </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairman of the council. He said final official results would not be announced until a recount is concluded Thursday. Agriculture Minister <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Morales </PERSON> <PERSON> Erlich </PERSON> estimated voter turnout at between 850,000 and 900,000 _ one of the lowest in Salvadoran history and less than half of those eligible. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador, had said a turnout of 60 percent or better would represent a defeat for the guerrilla strategy. <PERSON> Chavez </PERSON> <PERSON> Mena </PERSON> conceded that <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> would win more than 50 percent of the vote, thus enabling him to evade a runoff election that would have been held next month between the top two contendes. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said: `` Our relationship with that new government will depend on its adherence to democracy and respect for human rights, the twin pillars of our approach to <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>,'' said department spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> praised the <LOCATION> Salvadoran </LOCATION> people for braving `` violence and terror'' by leftist guerrillas who, he said, tried harder to disrupt Sunday's balloting than any other election here in seven years. White House Press Secretary <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the elections `` represent a strong desire by the people of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> for the ability to participate in the election process.'' But he said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was `` concerned about the level of guerrilla attacks and human rights abuses'' during the balloting. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has supported <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION> with $ 3.5 billion in aid this decade, and some congressmen have said the results leave much to be desired. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON>, a 41-year-old coffee-grower and businessman, said late Sunday he `` would be the president of all 5 million Salvadorans. We are going to unify this people in order to pull ourselves out of this profound crisis.'' <PERSON> Arena </PERSON> was linked in the early 1980s to rightist death squads blamed for the murders of tens of thousands of suspected leftists. <PERSON> Cristiani </PERSON> contends the party has changed significantly and his candidacy was evidence of that. But fanatical rightists remain prominent in the party, including party founder <PERSON> Roberto </PERSON> <PERSON> d'Aubuisson </PERSON>, who was once called a `` pathological killer'' by a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON> has repeatedly denied links to death squads. <PERSON> D'Aubuisson </PERSON>, a former army major who was cashiered in 1980 for allegedly plotting a coup, is an Arena legislator. Although he holds no formal party post, he was the party's top drawing card at election rallies, where he was introduced as `` maximum leader.'' The election marked the first time Salvadoran voters had a chance to replace an incumbent civilian government with a distinctly different government. Guerrillas of the <ORGANIZATION> Farabundo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marti </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> tried to thwart the voting with a transport ban across the Massachusetts-sized country and attacks on military positions in 12 of the country's 14 provinces. The insurgents lifted the ban Monday and said that the high absentee rate proved their contention that <PERSON> El </PERSON> <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON>'s problems could not be solved without their participation. At least 29 guerrillas and soldiers were killed in Sunday's fighting, as well as two civilians, according to Col. <PERSON> Emilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON>, chief of the joint chiefs of staff <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the attacks constituted `` a nationwide offensive.'' Three journalists _ two Salvadorans and a Dutchman _ also were killed and a fourth seriously wounded by security forces over election weekend.
