<TEXT>
 A former Methodist minister found financially liable for an attack that has left his wife comatose said he will honor a subpoena he was confronted with when he came to town to visit his children. <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> <PERSON> Railey </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> KDFW-TV </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> on Sunday that he has agreed to make his financial records available to the attorney who represents his wife's parents. <PERSON> Railey </PERSON> was served the subpoena Saturday morning as he approached the home of a friend who has custody of his two children. <PERSON> Railey </PERSON> said he was in town from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to help his children celebrate their March birthdays. No criminal charges have been filed in the April 21, 1987, attack on <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Railey </PERSON>. But in a civil suit filed by Mrs. <PERSON> Railey </PERSON>'s parents against <PERSON> Railey </PERSON>, a state district judge awarded nearly $ 18 million in a default judgment. <PERSON> Railey </PERSON> was served the suit twice, but never responded to the allegation that he attacked his wife, though he denied it out of court. Despite the judge's ruling, Mrs. <PERSON> Railey </PERSON>'s parents, <PERSON> William </PERSON> and <PERSON> Billie </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicolai </PERSON>, have yet to collect any money from <PERSON> Railey </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON>, the attorney for the Nicolais, subpoenaed <PERSON> Railey </PERSON> for questioning about his financial status last week. `` This is just part of the process. The judge found him liable for trying to kill his wife,'' said <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> said. `` This is just the next step in trying to find what assets he had. It will never make <PERSON> Peggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Railey </PERSON> whole, but it's the only thing we have left to do.'' <PERSON> Railey </PERSON> said he did n't respond to the earlier subpoenas because ``