<HEAD>`The Heidi Chronicles' Moves to Broadway; A Lackluster `Macbeth'
Off-Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> has made the journey from off-Broadway to <LOCATION> Broadway </LOCATION> with her wit and wisdom intact. In fact, she has gotten better, although she'd be the first to deny it. <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> is the insecure heroine of `` The <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> <PERSON> Chronicles </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Wendy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON>'s funny feminist travelogue that takes theatergoers from the late 1960s to the present. The play, now on view at Broadway's <ORGANIZATION> Plymouth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Theater </ORGANIZATION> after a successful run at Playwrights Horizons, remains one of the unqualified joys of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> theater season In a series of sketches, <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON> traces <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON>'s changing ideas about herself, about men and about other women. <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON>, an art historian, may not embrace every trend, notion or belief that pops up during her 20-year <PERSON> Odyssey </PERSON>, but she examines them with a discerning attitude that is rich in humor and not above a little anger. Director <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullivan </PERSON> has enlarged the production for Broadway, but he has n't diluted its effectiveness. Large slide projections that pinpoint specific historical moments _ from <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> War protests to the first rumbles of women's as well as gay liberation _ enhance its appeal. Snippets of old pop music also help anchor the play in the particular time periods. At the center of the play stands <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Allen </PERSON>'s radiant performance as <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON>. She projects an intelligence and likability that never waver during the character's many moments of self-doubt. It's a richly drawn portrait. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON> has polished his performance as the egocentric baby-boomer publisher who is in love with <PERSON> Heidi </PERSON> but marries someone else. He's arrogance at its most ingratiating. <PERSON> Boyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaines </PERSON> is funny and at times poignant as a sardonic but caring baby doctor. <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON>, the one new addition to the cast, demonstrates her virtuosity in two roles _ as a flower child in a hilarious women's rap session and as an ambitious corporate groupie of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> years. <PERSON> Wasserstein </PERSON> has had some off-Broadway successes, most notably `` Is n't It Romantic'' and `` Uncommon Women and Others.'' `` The Heidi Chronicles'' is her Broadway debut, and it's something to cheer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 American audiences deserve to see the Royal National Theater of <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, but not the company of actors sent overseas by its educational division with a ragtag version of `` Macbeth.'' The production, now on view at the Harry DeJur Playhouse, toured colleges and universities across the country before coming to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> for a two-week run. <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON>'s shortest play has been made even shorter in this production, performed at just over two hours with no intermission. It just seems longer. Director <PERSON> Nick </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> has a concept but not a play. This is bare bones <PERSON> Shakespeare </PERSON> _ with no scenery and tattered, grimy all-purpose costumes. Eight actors play all the roles. When not acting, they sit trance-like on benches located on three sides of the stage. That dispassion carries over to their performances. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Drury </PERSON>, a <PERSON> Nicol </PERSON> <PERSON> Williamson </PERSON> look-alike, possesses a resonant voice but it has little emotion. At least a quivering <PERSON> Amelda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> suggests <PERSON> Lady </PERSON> <PERSON> Macbeth </PERSON>'s obsession with power. Nothing else in this forlorn revival seems alive.
</TEXT>
