<HEAD>Telephone Sabotage, Computer Problems Hurt Vote Count</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sabotaged electrical and telephone service hampered election officials' plan for a quick vote count in the presidential election. The plan had been for each of more than 260 voting location in 14 provinces to transmit facsimiles of its returns by telephone to the national <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> in the capital Sunday night after the polls closed. Election officials had said they expected to have preliminary returns on election night. That turned out to be optimistic. At midnight on election night the council announced it was suspending the count because of `` technical'' problems with the computer. On Monday morning, <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Alberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Diaz </PERSON>, the council member who represents the rightist <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nationalist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION>, or <PERSON> Arena </PERSON>, told reporters that returns were not yet in from some areas affected by power outages. Leftist rebels lifted their transport ban on Monday, but on election day there were reports that returns could not be delivered because of dangerous conditions on the roads. Basic service like telephones and electricity are favorite guerrilla targets and more than half the nation's electrical grid is not working. Instead of trying to transmit the results by FAX, poll officials said, the ballots and tally sheets would have to be brought from all over this Massachusetts-sized to the capital. Final official results might not come until as late as Thursday. But even though official results were not available, the parties made predictions about the outcome based on unofficial results from their own poll watchers. Arena claimed victory with more than 50 percent of the vote Sunday, and the <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democrats </ORGANIZATION> conceded, even though only 130,000 votes had been officially counted at the t