<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs March 27 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>CONTINENT IN CRISIS: Peru _ A Threat of Civil War</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
 This is one of a series of periodic reports by The Associated Press on the economic, social and political turbulence that has turned <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> into a continent in crisis. In this report, the <ORGANIZATION> AP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> bureau </ORGANIZATION> chief in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> surveys <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, which has possibly reached the lowest point in its 165 years as an independent nation.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LIMA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 `` These are the days of the anonymous nocturnal bullet, of the slashing of throats of village officials, of the disappearance of union leaders.'' So wrote <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilderbrandt </PERSON> in a column recently in Si magazine in a passage that epitomizes the desperation of today's <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, a nation struggling with economic chaos and a savage leftist insurgency that threatens to explode into civil war. From cab drivers to congressmen, Peruvians are asking themselves what went wrong in their Andean country, which had one of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s strongest economies until the 1960s. _ More than 14,000 people have been killed in the nine-year uprising by the the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Shining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Path </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- Sendero Luminoso -RRB- guerrilla organization Blackouts and bombs have become part of daily life in <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. A paramilitary death squad has made its appearance. _ Inflation hit a record 1,722 percent in 1988 and is widely projected to soar above 10,000 percent this year, pushing wages and salaries down to bare-survival levels The economy shrank 9 percent in 1988 and is likely to contract even more this year. _ The collapse is putting hundreds of thousands of people out of work in the continent's third largest country and one of its poorest In 1976, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> produced 34,000 automobiles; this year it is expected to assemble, at the most, 3,500. Few people can afford them. Although many Peruvians blame President <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON> for the chaos, most independent analysts say the economic crisis had been building toward an eruption for the past several decades; <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>'s populist, free-spending policies lit the fuse Highway bandits have begun waylaying buses and automobiles, making travel outside <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> dangerous and adding to the sense of a disintegrating nation where law and order has broken down. Many Peruvians now speak of `` the civil war that is coming,'' seeing it as inevitable. `` There is a very real danger that <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, without realizing it, is sinking deeper into the swamps of fratricidal war,'' the magazine <PERSON> Oiga </PERSON> commented in a recent editorial. Surveys indicate most people have little faith that solutions will be found. <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, a dynamic young leader, was elected in 1985 as `` the president of hope.'' But his defiant stance against paying the foreign debt, now $ 19 billion, cut <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> off from international aid and his uncontrolled spending bankrupted the country, critics say. These days angry crowds shout `` <PERSON> Alan </PERSON>, you charlatan'' when he speeds by in heavily armed convoys. In recent months <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> has been hit by waves of coup rumors and many Peruvians doubt the presidential election scheduled for April 1990 will take place. Leftist military officers seized power in 1968; constitutional government was restored in 1980. Former Mayor <PERSON> Alfonso </PERSON> <PERSON> Barrantes </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, a Marxist, is one of the favorites in the campaign. The other front-runner is the writer <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON>, leader of a center-right coalition. Peruvians frequently mention the opening passage in <PERSON> Vargas </PERSON> <PERSON> Llosa </PERSON>'s 1974 novel `` Conversation in the Cathedral,'' saying it succinctly reflects their feelings now: `` From the doorway of <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cronica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> looks at the <LOCATION> Avenida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tacna </LOCATION> without love: cars, uneven and faded buildings, the gaudy skeletons of posters floating in the mist, the gray midday. At what precise moment had <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> -LRB- screwed -RRB- itself up?'' One who saw things that way was <PERSON> Morty </PERSON> <PERSON> Weisselberg </PERSON>, 41, a second-generation Peruvian, who had a high-paying job as the manager of a small metallurgical company. He packed up and left a few months ago for <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> with his wife and two small daughters. Before he left he explained why. `` What worries me is the kind of future I am going to leave my children. ` The future that this country offers is very different from the one 30 years ago when I was in the position of my children. Then there was a bright future for the country, at least apparently.'' The Weisselbergs were among 150,000 Peruvians, most of them professionals and skilled workers, who bought one-way tickets out the country in 1988, the largest exodus in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s history.
</TEXT>
