<SECOND>PM-Continent in Crisis-Peru, Adv 27-1st add,0567</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon PMs March 27 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>LIMA: Peru's history.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Many blame <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s economic decline on several decades of government mismanagement, controls that have stifled private enterprise and strident nationalism that has frightened away foreign investors and isolated <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> from world financial centers. More than anything, <PERSON> Weisselberg </PERSON> said before he left, he was frightened by what he saw as the country's deep class divisions and its growing violence. Political analysts agree with him that <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s social and racial divisions, inherited from the Spanish colonial era, have spawned class hatred that threatens to rip apart the fabric of Peruvian society. The scorn and discrimination shown by <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s white elite toward the dark-skinned Indian and mestizo majority has generated deep resentment among <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s poor, say social scientists. `` Political violence in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is not the result of poverty alone but of humiliation, oppression, class hatred, racism,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernales </PERSON>, head of a blue-ribbon <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel on violence. For many Peruvian and foreign political experts, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> now stands at a critical point in its 165-year history where an antiquated, inequitable and inefficient politial structure is crumbling. `` For me the Shining Path is nothing more than the violent natural expression of this social explosion,'' said <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Lumbreras </PERSON>, one of <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s most important archaeologists. `` If it had not been Shining Path, sooner or later there would have been another group,'' Lumbreras is from <LOCATION> Ayacucho </LOCATION>, the impoverished highland province where the Maoist-inspired guerrillas launched their insurgency in 1980, after 10 years of organizing among Quechua-speaking Indians in the countryside. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> covers an area larger than <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> combined and has a population of 21 million. But just as it is divided by class and race, it is sharrply divided by its geography into three regions _ the Andean sierra, the coastal deserts and the <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> rain forest _ that feel little in common with one another. In the 1950s highland peasants began to crowd into <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>, the capital, looking for a better life, and the migration has accelerated in recent years as the countryside has turned into a battlefield. With the Shining Path insurgency and the forced integration of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> and other coastal cities, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s white class has begun to feel challenged for the first time. Once the royal capital of the Spanish empire in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> is surrounded by the bleakest shantytowns on the continent, home to two-thirds of the city's 7 million inhabitants. <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s rich, increasingly insecure, live behind high walls in suburbs to which entry is controlled by gates and armed guards. The economic collapse, regarded as the worst in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s history, has hit the middle class and the poor the hardest. The purchasing power of salaries has plummeted by at least 50 percent in the last year. A doctor at a public hospital earns the equivalent of $ 80 a month. A public school teacher earns $ 55. The value of an army general's salary has fallen from $ 1,100 a month in 1980 to $ 200 today. <PERSON> Dorotea </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandoval </PERSON> lives with her husband and eight children in the shantytown of <LOCATION> Villa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, where mothers boil fish bones to give a thin broth to their children. `` We stopped eating meat a long time ago,'' she said.
</TEXT>
