<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Antarctica _ Shipwreck Revises U.S. Mission</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One of a four-story package. With b0729-b0730.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALMER STATION, Antarctica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 For two decades scientists enjoyed a cloistered existence at this <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> research center, studying wildlife in conditions as unspoiled as anywhere in the world. No longer. The mission of <ORGANIZATION> Palmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION>, perched on a gravelly point beneath a towering glacier, changed overnight when the Argentine supply ship <ORGANIZATION> Bahia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paraiso </ORGANIZATION> ran aground Jan. 28 and spilled its cargo of diesel fuel just offshore. `` This is changing from a place where people studied untouched nature long-term to a place where people study the effects of an oil spill long-term,'' said <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubega </PERSON>, an ornithologist from <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-Irvine </ORGANIZATION>. She was studying skuas and kelp gulls at the station when the wreck occurred. `` As an ecosystem that was basically undisturbed, it's a horrible loss. Really it's tragic,'' Miss <PERSON> Rubega </PERSON> said. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON>, an ornithologist from the <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reyes </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -RRB- Bird Observatory, said there already are indications of some poisoning of penguins, skuas, cormorants and other bird species that populate the rocky islands around the spill. `` We have no direct evidence of heavy mortality, but we have indirect evidence,'' he said. Scavanging giant petrels who live on the rocky islands around the base were feeding their newborn chicks an unusually rich diet of penguin meat after the spill, <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. `` What this means is you had large numbers of penguins dying locally.'' In addition, 726 pairs of polar skuas were nesting in the area when the spill occurred. `` Every single one lost their chicks,'' <PERSON> Frazer </PERSON> said. He stressed that the evidence was not conclusive. A team of 15 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> scientists has just begun more comprehensive studies. Ironically, the site offers an excellent base of information for a before-and-after examination of a spill. The wealth of data on bird and marine life collected since the station went into operation can be used for comparison, <PERSON> Fraser </PERSON> said. `` It's a terrible disaster, but it's an incredible natural experiment.''
</TEXT>
