<FIRST>s i BC-Antarctica-Glance Adv26   03-20 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Antarctica-Glance, Adv 26,0396</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Antarctica at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: One of a four-story package. With b0729-b0730.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are some facts and figures about <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>: HISTORY: <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s Capt. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Cook </PERSON> is believed to have first entered Antarctic waters during an expedition in 1773-75, and he was followed by several other mariners who discovered land there in the early 1800s. The American Capt. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkes </PERSON> first identified it as a continent in 1840 when he traced 1,500 miles of coastline. The first inland expeditions were carried out by <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Kristensen </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> Shackleton </PERSON> in the late 1800s and early 1900s. <PERSON> Roald </PERSON> <PERSON> Amundsen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> reached the <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pole </LOCATION> in December 1911 and <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> arrived a month later, but his four-man party perished.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 GEOGRAPHY: <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION> is 5.1 million square miles in area, larger than all of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and now has been determined to have 17,500 miles of rugged coastline. Its uneven surface of rock and gravel descends toward the center like a soup bowl, under the vast weight of a rounded cap of ice more than a mile deep in some places. The total volume of ice on the continent is equivalent to 72 percent of all water on earth. The continent is divided by the <LOCATION> Transantarctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Range </LOCATION> and includes other clusters of peaks including <PERSON> Visson </PERSON> <PERSON> Massif </PERSON>, the highest at 16,864 feet above sea level.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 CLIMATE: The coldest continent, <LOCATION> Antartica </LOCATION>'s inland temperatures remain almost constantly below freezing. On the <LOCATION> Antarctic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> temperatures can rise above freezing during the austral summer. The lowest reading ever, at the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s Vostok Station on July 21, 1983, was minus 89.2 degrees Celcius. There is little precipitation in <LOCATION> Antarctica </LOCATION>, averaging four inches a year.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 POLITICS: The continent is administered by the <ORGANIZATION> Antarctic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treaty </ORGANIZATION>, signed by 12 nations in 1961 who agreed to suspend all territorial claims and dedicate the region to peaceful research. Eight other nations have since become voting members, while 18 more enjoy observer status. The treaty is up for review in 1991. Seven nations make direct territorial claims to part of the continent, with some claims overlapping. Other countries, including The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, refuse to recognize any claims.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, March 26</NOTE>
