<FIRST>s i BC-China-OwningAHome Adv26   03-20 0939</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-China-Owning A Home, Adv 26,0970</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, March 26, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Owning a Home in China: A lot of Money for Little Space</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto Planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>YANTAI, China (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An ambitious experiment to allow <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> to own their homes has halted in this seaside city because of complaints from powerful officials and austerity policies in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Other experiments in housing reform throughout <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> are also off to a slow start due to the sky-high price of living space and lack of confidence in the government. `` The policies are in contradiction. We do n't know what the future holds,'' said <PERSON> Qin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shiyu </PERSON>, a housing reform official in <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION>, a breezy town in <LOCATION> Shandong </LOCATION> province on the <LOCATION> Bohai </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, apartments cost the equivalent of about $ 45 a square foot, meaning that an average college graduate would have to save his total income for 70 years to buy a basic three-room flat. In crowded <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> prices can be even higher. A recent report by the official <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said living space per person in a <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> neighborhood amounted to nine by nine feet, or 54 square feet. `` And that's only for the relatively well off,'' it said. Thousands, it said, were living in 21.6 square feet of space. In <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION>, prices have been more reasonable and 1,600 homes have been sold in about two years. But 16,000 families are still waiting for a chance to buy. <PERSON> Yu </PERSON> <PERSON> Bingmo </PERSON>, a worker at the <ORGANIZATION> Yantai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Synthetic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Leather </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Factory </ORGANIZATION>, was lucky. In October, he scraped together his life savings, took out a loan and bought his three-room, 600-square-foot apartment _ or about 30 feet by 20 feet _ for about 12,000 yuan -LRB- $ 3,243 -RRB-. `` It may mean a few more years of lousy cigarettes but I was willing to take the risk,'' said <PERSON> Yu </PERSON>, 57, as he sat with his wife in the living room. `` It's not a palace but at least it's mine.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> began housing reform in the mid-1980s in an attempt to correct a serious housing shortage that had left millions of Chinese urban dwellers with nowhere to live. The plan picked up urgency over the past few years as part of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s effort to reform its heavily subsidized housing system. In <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s countryside, houses are privately owned and passed from generation to generation. But in the cities, home to 40 percent of the country's 1.1 billion people, housing has been built and maintained by state funds and rented at rock-bottom prices. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s housing industry is a welfare undertaking making no profits at all,'' said a recent edition of the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Review. <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> also looked at private housing as a way to channel people's money into the country's infrastructure and halt spending on consumer goods They reasoned that less consumer spending would limit record high inflation of around 30 percent. In addition, reformers wanted to battle corrupt officials who use their power to secure bigger and better apartments for themselves and their friends. In 1986, <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION> and three other cities were selected as the first group of pilot cities for urban housing reform. In <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION>, rent was raised almost 2000 percent to 1.24 yuan a square meter -LRB- 3 cents a square foot -RRB-. To Chinese accustomed to paying around 3 percent of their salaries for rent the jump was substantial. Next, the housing department ordered businesses in the city to add a subsidy of 23.5 percent of each worker's salary to his paycheck to make up for the rent increase. As rent payments to work units increased, the state cut the amount it gave them for housing. Residents were also made responsible for the upkeep of their homes. `` You've got a broken toilet, well fix it yourself,'' said <PERSON> Wang </PERSON> <PERSON> Qingyuan </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Estate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION>. `` The end result is that people are being made more responsible for their lives.'' Workers were encouraged to buy their houses at cut-rate prices, one-tenth to one-fifth of the market rate. Special low - or no-interest loans were offered To discourage speculation, resale was permitted only after five years. The sales pace was quick. But, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s economy was overheating. To cut spending, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s Cabinet, ordered all money received in the sales of housing frozen in bank accounts for two years. And the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> clamped a 40 percent tax on those funds. Other problems were brewing. <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION>, known for its clean air and fresh fish, is a retirement area for some of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s most powerful former officials. When rents went up, they complained. Some went on rent strikes, others used `` connections'' to avoid paying. The effect on <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION>'s reform was deadening. Work units, which own all the housing, stopped selling. A halt in sales meant housing construction stopped. `` We were like a truck moving downhill and then somebody slammed on the brakes,'' said one official. `` It was a pretty big shock.'' Other cities, like <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, have also begun housing reform but to them it only means putting a few houses on the market. Their success has been even less notable than <LOCATION> Yantai </LOCATION>'s. Because housing prices are so high and no attempts have been made to change the rent system, only successful individual businessmen, still a rarity in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, are able to afford their own home. On a recent afternoon, <PERSON> Sun </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaofeng </PERSON>, a cab driver who makes 300 yuan -LRB- $ 81 -RRB- a month, a good deal by Chinese standards, strolled into the <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Real Estate Exchange. `` I'm just curious,'' he said. `` I'll never be able to buy a house, not in 10,000 years.''
</TEXT>
