 `` A Summer to Remember'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> Home Video. VHS-Beta, $ 39.95. Rated PG -RRB- `` A Summer to Remember'' does have <PERSON> Tess </PERSON> <PERSON> Harper </PERSON>, a cute orangutan and a couple of kids who triumph over adults. But it is so syrupy that it's hard to swallow. The film, directed by <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, is about a deaf boy -LRB- <PERSON> Sean </PERSON> <PERSON> Gerlis </PERSON> -RRB- who feels isolated and extremely angry after his dad leaves him and his mother -LRB- <PERSON> Harper </PERSON> -RRB- and sister. His stepfather -LRB- <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Farentino </PERSON> -RRB- tries desperately to reach him and break him from his shell. But what it takes to bring him out is an unlikely relationship he and his sister develop with an escaped ape who has been trained to speak in sign language. It's a clever idea, and the acting is fine. Also in the cast are <PERSON> Louise </PERSON> <PERSON> Fletcher </PERSON>, <PERSON> Burt </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> and <PERSON> Bridgette </PERSON> <PERSON> Andersen </PERSON>. The movie deals well with the difficulties that can develop between a stepfather and stepson, and with the way the world can seem to a deaf boy. But it hits the audience over the head with its good intentions. Especially heavy-handed are the music and and a slow-motion scene in which the kids tumble in a field with their orangutan pal.
