 `` Born to Burn'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> MCA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- _ <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Shameless </PERSON> <PERSON> Hussies </PERSON> <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> and the Shameless Hussies, working at some lonesome intersection where the Andrews Sisters meet <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Wills </PERSON>, are really a lot more talented than the dopey names and outrageous outfits would have you believe. In fact, that's the problem here _ the joke quickly wears thin, pulling down what could be a real up-and-coming country band with a difference. `` Ethel'' and her polyester pals, `` Bunni'' and `` Blanche,'' we are led to believe, are three good ol' gals who were all married to the same lout. They sing clever things _ `` I Thought He Was Mr. Right, But He Left'' _ and wear a lot of animal prints and semi-naughty corsets. But amid the schlock, there is some quality. Their singing is right on the mark, and their sound leans to <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> swing, the rebirth of which is the happiest country music trend in a long time. In real life, <PERSON> Ethel </PERSON> even comes with credentials: She's actually the songwriter <PERSON> Kacey </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, who co-wrote the <PERSON> Mickey </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilley </PERSON> hit `` I'm the One Mama Warned You About,'' which is reprised on `` Born to Burn.'' These women, though, face a big decision: Is this a country band or a vaudeville act? The gimmick that got them their big break is going to turn them into the <PERSON> Buster </PERSON> <PERSON> Poindexter </PERSON> of C & amp; W if thy do n't find a way out real fast _ By <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 `` Mystery Girl'' -LRB- Virgin -RRB- <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON>'s sudden death last December makes it hard to objectively consider this `` comeback album.'' Is it really good, or does sentimentality make it seem so? It's really good. Not perfect, but it would have been a hit even if <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON> had n't succumbed to a heart attack. <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON> imports an all-star crew to help him, including <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Petty </PERSON> and most of his Heartbreakers, <PERSON> Bono </PERSON> and The Edge of U2, <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynne </PERSON>, <PERSON> Elvis </PERSON> <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>, <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cropper </PERSON> and a host of studio stars. All <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON> needed to bring was that sweet, other-worldly voice. `` You Got It,'' the single, is successful for the same reason as the Traveling Wilburys _ it's light, breezy `` feel good'' pop. But the meat of the album are the <PERSON> Bono </PERSON> and Edge-composed `` She's a Mystery to Me'' and <PERSON> Costello </PERSON>'s `` The Comedians. The spare arrangement of the former lays bare a tale of romantic torment. `` The Comedians'' adds a bizarre new twist to romantic loss: The narrator is left stuck on the top of a ferris wheel while his girlfriend walks off holding the operator's hand. The song builds to a dramatic climax before <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON> leaves the listener, like himself, hanging in mid-air. Each of the album's 10 songs go down easily, with only `` -LRB- All I Can Do Is -RRB- Dream You'' having much of a rock' n' roll kick. That eventually becomes a problem. Songs such as `` A Love So Beautiful,'' `` Windsurfer'' and `` The Only One'' are predictable and tend to blend together after awhile. <PERSON> Orbison </PERSON> was successful when he tackled challenging material; he should have tried it a few more times. Still, this Rock' n' Roll Hall of Fame member managed to thrust himself onto the contemporary scene without looking foolish. That happens less often than it seems. _ By <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bauder </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Lieder by <PERSON> Franz </PERSON> <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON>; <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Battle </PERSON>, soprano, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, Piano -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Deutsche </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grammaphon </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Battle </PERSON> and <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Levine </PERSON> present a varied selection of Schubert songs, spanning a broad emotional range. In the first half, <ORGANIZATION> Battle </ORGANIZATION> sings mostly about the sunnier side of love. Her light, supple voice is perfectly suited to <PERSON> Schubert </PERSON>'s setting of <PERSON> Goethe </PERSON>'s `` Liebhaber in allen Gestalten,'' with its repeated line, `` Would that I were a fish, so nimble and agile. Those words nicely sum up Battle's fine voice. Her instrument changes color for the interesting `` An die Laute,'' in which a young man confides his love to a lute. <PERSON> Levine </PERSON>, whose pianism is as welcome as his podium work, perfectly approximates the sound of the lute in the accompaniment. This recording amply demonstrates that Battle does not lack for charm, and does not hesitate to show it. The listener is won over on the eighth track, a hauntingly beautiful lullaby called `` Nacht und Traume.'' She sings softly throughout with a heart-aching sweetness. The song is about the joy men take in their dreams, and ends with a depressing conclusion _ a call for a return to sleep when day breaks. The program now takes a darker turn. Battle sings of aching hearts in `` Rastlose Liebe,'' or `` restless love,'' and the turbulent night of a young nun awaiting her Saviour like a trembling bride in `` Die junge Nonne.'' Finally comes the wondrous `` Shepherd on the Rock,'' which transverses the range of a lover's emotions _ yearning, grief, loneliness, longing and the joy of anticipation. To some tastes, this song is better for a deeper voice, and Battle has trouble with some of the low notes. But she sings with conviction and attention to detail. Clarinettist <PERSON> Karl </PERSON> <PERSON> Leister </PERSON> is flawless, sounding like a cool mountain stream bubbling over polished rocks. _ By <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Wakin </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> Writer.
