<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: With Bicentennial-Museums</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Just about every museum in <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> is putting on an exhibition to mark the bicentennial of the French Revolution. Among them: `` Magicians of the Earth'' is the theme covering contemporary art works from both industrialized and developing countries at the <LOCATION> Pompidou </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Center </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Grande </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Halle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Villette </ORGANIZATION>. The show runs May through August. Fashion-lovers can view clothes from aristocratic closets of the revolutionary period in the Musee de la Mode et du Costume, <PERSON> Palais </PERSON> <PERSON> Galliera </PERSON>, until May 7. Emphasis is on `` The Stuff of Heroes'' at the <ORGANIZATION> Musee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> des </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> et de la Mode in the Decorative Arts wing of the <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION>. The May to August exhibition will spotlight revolutionary-period clothes with an emphasis on textiles, accessories and jewelry. The most striking art from the revolutionary period will be the paintings and drawings by <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> displayed at the <LOCATION> Louvre </LOCATION>, Oct. 26 to Feb. 12, 1990. The works by this `` realist'' artist and chronicler of the times include a sketch of a hook-nosed and grim Marie-Antoinette on her way to the guillotine.
</TEXT>
