<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: With Oklahoma-Indians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A taste of the Old West awaits the tour group that will travel through what was once <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> territory, meeting tribal elders and sharing their lives for a few days. Led by anthropologist <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vetter </PERSON>, a select group of about 12 people will learn about Indian values and spirituality, visit Indian sacred sites, and view and participate in tribal pow-wows. The group will explore <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> and take part in the `` sweat lodge,'' an ancient ritual of purification. They also will learn how to set up, take down and travel with teepees. The tour, `` Journey in Indian Territory,'' runs May 3 through May 10. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON>, a Pawnee Indian and adjunct instructor of anthropology at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION>, will accompany the tour. <PERSON> Vetter </PERSON> has studied and written about <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> culture, working with <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Pahdopony </PERSON>, the last medicine man of the Comanche Indians. <PERSON> Vetter </PERSON> says that <LOCATION> Indian </LOCATION> people practice `` fictive kinship,'' meaning they extend kinship ties to people who are not blood relatives. He says he feels related this way to some of the Indians he has met and worked with. Yet he says he does not try to romanticize Indian life. `` They are a people of the 1990s, as well as a people of the 1860s, with the same inherent faults and virtues as the rest of us.'' Cost is $ 695 per person, covering orientation, registration, lodging, instructions, lectures, activities, some meals and ground transportation.
