<FIRST>a a BC-SPE--Travel:AranIslands     03-20 0642</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-SPE--Travel: Aran Islands,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Aran Islands</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY701</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KILRONAN, Aran Islands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Aran </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> have so many stone walls that only seeing is believing. The three inhabited islands _ <LOCATION> Inishmore </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Inishmaan </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Inisheer </LOCATION> _ add up to about 18 square miles, but there must be hundreds of miles of stone walls. They are usually dry walls of mostly sharp stones enclosing tiny pastures and gardens. The walls are the key to the makeup of the <LOCATION> Aran </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>, lying across the mouth of the Bay of <LOCATION> Galway </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>'s west coast. They are islands of limestone, solidified sediment of a tropical sea that covered the area more than 270 million years ago. Documentary filmmaker <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON>, in `` Man of Aran'' -LRB- filmed on Inishmaan in the 1930s -RRB-, showed viewers what seemed the epitome of isolation and struggle against the odds of nature. The islands also inspired playwright <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Millington </PERSON> <PERSON> Synge </PERSON>, author of `` Riders to the Sea'' and `` The Playboy of the Western World,'' when he visited in the 19th century. He made the trip from <LOCATION> Galway </LOCATION> by curragh, the native open Irish canoe made of timber lathes and canvas and rowed by two or more people. Although the islands are only about six miles from <LOCATION> Doolin </LOCATION>, in <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clare </LOCATION>, and some 30 miles from <LOCATION> Galway </LOCATION>, they must have seemed remote indeed. But today, <PERSON> Kilronan </PERSON>, the main village on the biggest island, Inishmore, can seem quite crowded by people looking for the remote. Boats bring day trippers from <LOCATION> Rossaveal </LOCATION>, north of <LOCATION> Galway </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Doolin </PERSON>. Both boat trips are far shorter than the three hours it takes the boat from <LOCATION> Galway </LOCATION>. The bed-and-breakfasts in the <LOCATION> Aran </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> have television, hot water, electricity and radiators in the bedrooms. But the Aran Islands are still a world of their own _ and still remote in their way _ for visitors who spend days rather than hours on them, walking and looking around and listening to the Gaelic language. A horse cart, van or bike will take a visitor to the foot of the hill where stands <PERSON> Dun </PERSON> <PERSON> Aengus </PERSON>, one of the best preserved prehistoric fort-like structures in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. The climb to the top has to be done on foot, across a wet, rock-strewn meadow with dainty little flowers and over rocks worn so smooth by nature and so criss-crossed by little crevices that they resemble giant tiles. They are slippery in wet weather _ and chances are it will be misting if not raining there or anywhere else on the <LOCATION> Aran </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION>. In addition to the stone walls, stone ruins and stone houses, stone crosses dot the landscape, in memory of islanders killed at sea. Fishing is still a major occupation of the islanders and the sea still rules their lives. The man running the tourist office may suddenly shoo away the tourists, close down, and dash to the beach where others, clad in orange rescue suits, are already launching a motorized rescue raft for a boat in trouble under the cliffs of Moher, across the water in <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Clare </LOCATION>. As dusk falls on Inishmeer, on a broad sand beach, small boys play with their dogs. The friendly donkeys no longer used for tilling the soil come up to nuzzle a passerby. There are piles of curraghs on the beach, for Inishmeer is the only place in the islands where they're still made. Beyond the beach, on a sweep of dune, are an old burying ground and various ruins dating back to medieval times or even earlier. Up a steep hill, one comes upon a cashel wall -LRB- ancient circular wall that used to enclose ecclesiastical buidings -RRB- and within it a `` more modern'' tower house built, perhaps, in the late 14th century. Alone in the misty twilight, visitors can still feel the remoteness of time and place.
</TEXT>
