<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Agents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PRUDENCE HELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans made 1.2 billion person trips in 1987, according to the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. A person trip is travel by one person a distance of 100 miles or more from home. Whether they traveled for business or pleasure, many depended on a travel agent for help. Who are these travel agents? <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> Walker </PERSON>, in her 20s, works for the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motorists </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> travel agency in <LOCATION> Oberlin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>. It's one of 27 association branches throughout the state. Miss <PERSON> Walker </PERSON> headed for the travel business straight out of high school, lured by her love of travel, an interest in geography and the prospect of free or cut-rate trips. A school in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> that offered a six-week crash course plus six months of home study sent her on her way. <PERSON> Kaye </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, a vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Barnett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tours </ORGANIZATION> and Cruises in <LOCATION> Greensboro </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION>, has been in the business more than 25 years. She went into the travel field after trying and discarding nursing and banking. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> Chipman </PERSON>, co-owner of the Encore <PERSON> Preston </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> travel agency in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, was divorced and in her 30s when she went to work about 25 years ago for a friend who owned a travel agency. It was a traditional business for women without specialized training to enter when they wanted something to do after the children were grown, much like real estate, Mrs. <PERSON> Chipman </PERSON> explained in a telephone interview. But computerization has changed all that, she said, and most travel agencies do n't have much time for in-house training these days. To get a job, one needs computer know-how. She also notes that more and more men are entering the field, especially at management level. Both Mrs. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> and Mrs. <PERSON> Chipman </PERSON> are certified travel counselors -LRB- CTC -RRB-, meaning they have taken courses offered by the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Certified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> ICTA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, a non-profit organization headquartered in <LOCATION> Wellesley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, devoted to educating travel industry personnel. To earn the initials, an agent must have completed a five-part travel management program, served at least five years in the travel industry and signed a code of ethics. The <ORGANIZATION> ICTA </ORGANIZATION> also has started a new program of training in geographical areas that will allow agents who complete the course to use the desination DS, or destination specialist. A <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> survey for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> ASTA </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, showed that the gross dollar volume of all bookings handled by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> travel firms in 1987 was $ 64.2 billion. And yet, it seems, there is relatively little formal regulation in the field. A spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> ASTA </ORGANIZATION>'s state <ORGANIZATION> legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> department </ORGANIZATION> says only seven states regulate agents and agencies, with the regulations varying state-to-state. The seven are <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. Various organizations within the industry itself, including <ORGANIZATION> ASTA </ORGANIZATION>, have codes of ethics for members. <ORGANIZATION> ASTA </ORGANIZATION>'s covers such things as accuracy of any information an agent gives out, full information to travelers about terms and conditions of any sale, and prompt remittance of any undisputed funds. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is owned by major <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> airlines and serves as a clearing house for receipts that agents get from airline tickets they sell. It also sets standards for the agents with which it has agreements _ more than 33,600 of them. If an agency does not live up to its agreement, <ORGANIZATION> ARC </ORGANIZATION> can pull the `` plates'' through which it makes out airline tickets. The <ORGANIZATION> ICTA </ORGANIZATION> quotes estimates that there are about 200,000 travel agents across the country waiting to help travelers. Usually, their services are free. And they say that especially in this day of airline deregulation, agents can save the traveler time and money with their computers, contacts and background. But how many travelers actually follow the advice to `` see your travel agent''? Relatively few, according to the <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. It estimates that 13 percent of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> travelers consulted an agent in 1987 and of those, only 10 percent used them to book hotel or airline reservations. <ORGANIZATION> ASTA </ORGANIZATION>, however, estimates that almost 90 percent of cruises are booked through travel agencies, and 80 percent of airline travel. But it estimates bookings of hotels through agents only in the mid-20 percent range, with most of that for hotels outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.
