<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: With Agents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 How can those who want to use a travel agent find a good one? The <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Certified </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION>, a non-profit organization headquartered in <LOCATION> Wellesley </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, and devoted to educating travel industry personnel, offers some advice:. `` First, ask a friend who's had a good experience with an agent.'' It also suggests that one look for the <ORGANIZATION> CTC </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- certified travel counselor -RRB- or DS -LRB- destination specialist -RRB- designations, given by <ORGANIZATION> ICTA </ORGANIZATION> to those who have completed its courses. Also, <ORGANIZATION> ICTA </ORGANIZATION> says, membership of an agency in such trade associations as <ORGANIZATION> ASTA </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> ARTA </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Travel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agents </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- is an indicator of a serious-minded agent. Note, too, how long the agency has been in the field, and how long its staff has been in the business. Beware of rapid turnover. And note whether the office is neat, well-stocked with brochures and well organized, and whether the staff is helpful and friendly.
