<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 `` Staying on schedule'' is the key to keeping healthy while traveling, says two specialists at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. That means eating, sleeping and bathroom habits, according to Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON> and Dr. O.H. <PERSON> Rundell </PERSON>. The two have these suggestions for reducing health problems while traveling: _ Stay on your regular schedule when eating. If you get constipated, do n't wait days to do something about it. Snacking on fruits and vegetables will help. _ Restrict your intake of rich foods, to prevent heartburn. _ If your travel keeps you away three or more days, catch up on your sleep before leaving. _ When crossing several time zones, use short-acting sleeping pills to help you sleep. _ Do n't drink to induce sleep on airplane flights. Instead, read a book or listen to music or relaxation tapes. <PERSON> Rankin </PERSON> is associate professor of medicine, <ORGANIZATION> Digestive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diseases </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nutrition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Section </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Memorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>; <PERSON> Rundell </PERSON> is adjunct assistant professor of psychiatry and behavioral sciences at the <ORGANIZATION> OU </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sciences </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and director of a sleep disorders center. For diabetics, Dr. <PERSON> Ira </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Laufer </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Diabetes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treatment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unit </ORGANIZATION> at the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Eye and <LOCATION> Ear </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Infirmary </LOCATION>, has some specific suggestions: _ Self-monitor your blood glucose, either by a test strip or electronically with a meter. _ Pack enough medication for several days in a carry-on bag. _ Keep a copy of any prescription with you at all times. _ For international travel, find out if waivers are needed to carry medication or syringes through Customs. _ See if your doctor can recommend a physician in your travel area. Travel agents can help with information on international medical and assistance services. _ Wear an emergency medical ID bracelet or necklace.
