<HEAD>Travel: With Health-Guide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 You have a broken leg, and you have a long flight ahead of you. You should have your cast split to prevent buildup of painful air pressure. You're a dieter, on the road. Only calorie-laden menus are presented to you. Be assertive; ask for what you need to maintain your diet. You want to avoid jet lag. You ca n't, but you can learn to handle it. This advice and other ways to travel in good health are covered in a new book, `` Travel Well, A Gourmet Guide to Healthy Travel'' -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Brontosaurus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, written by a <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> physician, <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON>, and his wife, <PERSON> Audrey </PERSON>. Travel, the <ORGANIZATION> Kaplans </ORGANIZATION> point out, can be hazardous to your health. Business travel can be stressful. You get less sleep and rest. You eat and drink too much. You do n't exercise enough. `` It is hard enough for people to control their weight, blood pressure, cholesterol level, exercise conditioning, and psychological equilibrium in the relatively stable home situation. On the road, it can be almost impossible,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Kaplans </ORGANIZATION> write. Their book includes advice about how to deal with these problems aloft and on the ground. To help travelers continue exercise and diet regimens, they list hotels with workout, jogging and swimming facilities and restaurants they say will prepare diet fare for you. The Kaplans say there is no proven way to fend off jet lag, but that it will help to try sleeping earlier on eastward flights and staying awake later on westward flights. To avoid stress, they advise planning, traveling light with carry-on luggage, and using special services such as business centers at airports.
