<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Business travel has become a big ticket item for many corporations, and many of them are learning to manage their own or to cut deals to cut rising travel costs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corporations are expected to spend over $ 115 billion on travel and entertainment in 1990, up from an estimated $ 95 billion last year, according to an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> survey. A similar survey by <ORGANIZATION> Runzheimer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> puts the median per-company travel expenditure for 1987 at $ 2,348,000, a rise of about $ 120,000 over the previous two years. Travel and entertainment costs are the third largest controllable expense for most companies, after salaries and data processing, <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> says. One way companies are dealing with travel expenses is to do it themselves, by adding in-house travel specialists to their staffs. About 29 percent of the 1,600 companies surveyed by <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> say they added travel managers in l988, an increase of 16 percent in two years. Many companies have computerized reservation equipment on their premises. Coupled with frequent reviews and closer enforcement of travel policies, their travel costs continue to rise, but at a rate less than overall average travel costs, according to <ORGANIZATION> Runzheimer </ORGANIZATION>, a travel and living cost consulting company. `` Employers are finally realizing how much they're spending on travel, and they're zeroing in on ways to control this major expense,'' says <PERSON> Bradford </PERSON> <PERSON> Burris </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Runzheimer </ORGANIZATION> publisher. Still, nine out of 10 companies use travel agencies, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> survey shows. Heavy spending companies are able to get lower fares and better services by consolidating the number of agencies they use. About half use a single agency. But even when they use outside agencies, more companies have become more directly involved in travel and entertainment expense management.
