<DATELINE>WATERLOO, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, in one place, you can contemplate 18th-century agricultural life, 19th-century industry, and 20th-century music. <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Village </LOCATION> is a restored rural village with buildings spanning two centuries, offering the visitor a visible historic time chart. Houses and outbuildings in rusticated stones from the 1740s show how the homesteaders who settled here along the banks of the <LOCATION> Musconetcong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> milled grain by water power and worked their trades as weavers, tavern keepers, blacksmiths, apothecaries and the like. Iron was found in the region, and by the time of the Revolutionary War, <LOCATION> Andover </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forge </LOCATION> in the village was producing gun barrels for the <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>. In 1815, Brig Gen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, an early landowner, renamed the community to celebrate <LOCATION> Wellington </LOCATION>'s victory over <PERSON> Napoleon </PERSON> at <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> that year The opening of the 102-mile <ORGANIZATION> Morris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> in the 1830s marked the next era, with <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> serving as an inland port for barges transporting coal, iron and grain from <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> to the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. The barges have gone now, but the towpaths remain for walking through forests, along lakes and rivers. Tall Victorian mansion houses also remain as a legacy of <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION>'s mid-19th century prosperity. <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION> declined with the coming of the railroads after the 1840s and nearly disappeared after the market crash in 1929. But the abandoned village was discovered by <PERSON> Percival </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON> and <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gualandi </PERSON> in the 1940s, and they began its restoration. The two men, partners in a design firm, solicited money for restoration and antiques for the 11,000-acre property, turning it into a historical museum now owned jointly by the state and the non-profit <ORGANIZATION> Waterloo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>. Music festivals are the 20th-century contribution to <LOCATION> Waterloo </LOCATION>. Its summer concert series began 20 years ago, and since then both classic and popular artists have entertained more than 250,000 visitors each year.
