<HEAD>SPECIAL EDITION</HEAD>
<HEAD>Travel: Amex Survey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Being with the family is the primary reason most Americans go on vacation, according to an <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Express </ORGANIZATION> survey. The survey of 1,000 adults found that 72 percent of those asked put family as the biggest motivation in taking a vacation, especially among women and among those over 65. It was followed by being with a spouse or companion, then rest and relaxation and escape from stress. Rest and relaxation was the biggest reason among travelers aged 18 through 49. Fifty-eight percent said they went on vacation for fun and entertainment and 56 percent wanted to `` go somewhere new.'' Men ranked romance higher than women did; 38 percent of the men said it was an important factor, compared to 32 percent of the women. The survey, called `` Psychology of Vacation Travel,'' also found that the average American vacationer takes a day-and-a-half to `` unwind,'' although nearly 10 percent said they never unwind. The vacation `` afterglow'' lasts six days, on the average, according to those interviewed. But 9 percent said it lasts less than a day. Others reasons cited for vacations included adventure, meeting new people, `` escape'' -LRB- from everyone, everything or the weather -RRB-, shopping and gambling.
</TEXT>
