<FIRST>r f PM-Europe-Inflation     03-20 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Europe-Inflation,0732</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inflation Heats Up In Europe Again</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Market Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By COTTEN TIMBERLAKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Inflation has been heating up in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for the first time in years and that, plus the higher interest rates being used to combat it, are causing a lot of worry across the Continent. But few economists believe <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> will return to double-digit inflation or that it will threaten the European economies' comeback of the late 1980s. The pickup in prices, which coincides with a resurgence in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation, is being blamed on faster-than-expected economic growth, which caught European governments by surprise. Central banks across <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, it turned out, slackened their grip too much after the October 1987 stock market crash, economists said. Both consumer buying and investment spending have been strong in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> and as a result, factories have been working at or near capacity. Economists also blame the upward trend in the dollar and the weakness of <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> currencies _ particularly the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> German </LOCATION> mark _ last year, as well as higher commodity prices, especially for oil. Higher prices are being exacerbated by higher wage claims, threatening to cause wage-price spirals in some countries. Since the second half of 1988, European countries have tried to stop inflation by raising interest rates to discourage that spending and borrowing, but there is no clear indication it is working. Signs are that consumers are continuing to spend. In <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, for example, retail sales spurted 2.5 percent in February. This renewed inflation is a big disappointment for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> following the great successes the once-lumbering and mature economies have had in turning themselves around by making their industries more modern and efficient. `` There are inflationary pressures within most of the economies in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. I think the inflation fear is fairly widespread,'' said <PERSON> Nigel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rendell </PERSON>, an economist at the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> James </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Capel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. European inflation will peak at 5 percent this year, its highest level since 1985, up from with 3.5 percent last year, he predicted It should fall back to 4 percent next year, as <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic growth slows and the dollar weakens, he said. <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> are expected to fare the worst, with an average annual rate of up to 7 percent in 1989, economists say. The continental economies are not as overheated as those of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, an economist with the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Kleinwort </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grieveson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>. As a result, inflation is `` a much easier problem for them to contend with,'' he said Indeed, <PERSON> Rendell </PERSON> said: `` It's important to stress that although we're going to get back to inflation, we're not going to get back to the teen-age -LRB- double-digit -RRB- inflation we saw in the 1970s or the double-digit inflation we saw earlier in the 1980s.'' Many economists think interest rates will have to go even higher, particularly after the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government reported Friday that wholesale prices surged 1 percent in February, prompting the stock markets to plunge. The rates might go up within the month, they said. But <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowers </PERSON>, an economist at <ORGANIZATION> Barclays </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoete </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wedd </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, said he is not convinced higher interest rates will work in <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, for example, because Spanish consumers are n't heavily indebted and because a large amount of investment is foreign and funded from the outside. In addition, these high rates, besides squeezing mortgage holders and other borrowers, are boosting currencies, and that is worsening trade imbalances in <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>. However, economists are not concerned that the higher interest rates will lead to a recession. `` In <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, there is a lot of -LRB- economic -RRB- momentum,'' <PERSON> Rendell </PERSON> said. `` We see -LRB- economic -RRB- growth at relatively high levels. It will be less than last year, but it still will be pretty strong.'' <PERSON> Rendell </PERSON> expects economic growth of 3 percent in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> this year compared with 4 percent in 1988. Here are annual inflation rates for 1988, and forecasts for 1989 and 1990 for the major <LOCATION> European </LOCATION> countries. They were provided by <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Capel </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> _ <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, 1.2 percent, 2.9 percent, 2 percent _ <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, 2.7 percent, 3.2 percent, 2 percent _ <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, 4.9 percent 7.1 percent, 4.5 percent _ <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, 5 percent, 6.5 percent, 6 percent _ <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, 4.9 percent,
