<HEAD>Lazare Kaplan Diamond Deal Sign of Hopefulness in Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN LINNEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A multimillion dollar agreement to import <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s diamonds announced this month by New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Lazare </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kaplan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> could translate into more than just much-needed hard currency to the war-ravaged southern African nation. Under terms negotiated with <ORGANIZATION> Endiama </ORGANIZATION>, the Angolan state diamond company, <PERSON> Lazare </PERSON> <PERSON> Kaplan </PERSON> will import $ 20 million a year in high-quality, uncut gem diamonds for processing at its plant in <LOCATION> Caguas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Puerto </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rico </LOCATION>, company spokeswoman <PERSON> Amy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wiener </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wiener </PERSON> said the first shipment has arrived for cutting and polishing in the plant. The agreement is the first major international business deal announced with the Marxist-oriented government since the signature Dec. 22 of U.S.-brokered accords by <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> on the phased withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. The withdrawal is being made in return for the independence of the South African-controlled territory of <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, formerly known as <LOCATION> South-West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. `` I was impressed by the fact that all those with whom we met in <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION> took a business-like, non-ideological approach,'' <ORGANIZATION> LKI </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> Tempelsman </PERSON> said in a company news release. `` In view of the close diplomatic cooperation between the American and Angolan authorities in connection with the withdrawal of South African and Cuban forces from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>, there is no reason why this agreement should not be followed by many mutually beneficial examples of economic cooperation between our two countries.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has no diplomatic relations with <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, which gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975 after a 14-year colonial war and has since been fighting U.S.-and South African-backed rebels. Ms. <PERSON> Wiener </PERSON> said the diamond importing agreement, the first LKI has made with <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, was indirectly related to the December accords. `` The peace process was moving forward, and continues to move forward,'' she said. `` It can only help business, and we're encouraged by it. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to stop supporting <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> and his <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> continues to supply about $ 15 million a year in military aid through bases in neighboring <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. Before his inauguration, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> assuring him of continued <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support in order to pressure Angolan President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> into negotiating. Nearly 90 percent of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s hard currency earnings come from oil pumped mainly by an Angolan-American consortium in fields near the mouth of the <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>. Under Portuguese rule, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> was exporting between 5 percent and 8 percent of the world's diamond production. Exports fell following independence but rose in 1981-82 to 1.3 million carats worth $ 165 million. In 1987 the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> company SPE -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Portuguese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entrepreneurial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- signed a cooperation agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Endiama </ORGANIZATION>, and 50 Portuguese technicians are working in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> as diamond mining advisers. A delegation from <ORGANIZATION> Endiama </ORGANIZATION> visited <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> earlier this month following a trip to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and there have been newspaper reports here of a possible joint venture between <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> in mining and finishing. Throughout the 1980s <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> has been an illicit export route for unfinished Angolan diamonds. The <LOCATION> Lisbon </LOCATION> daily <PERSON> Europeu </PERSON> said the illicit trade amounted to $ 200 million in 1983 alone. In 1984, Savimbi-led rebels attacked diamond mines in northeastern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, and production fell off sharply. The area was later divided into production blocs and leased to mining companies in the same way <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> has awarded concessions to oil companies. The Angolan army now provides security in the diamond-mining areas. Ms. <PERSON> Wiener </PERSON> said LKI does not plan to become involved in actual diamond mining in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>.
