<UNK>Shares Down, Dollar Up</UNK>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices plunged today in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> for their sharpest one-day decline this year, and the dollar gained against the Japanese yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, a 77.01-point loser Friday, shed another 366.21 points, or 1.14 percent, to finish trading at 31,654.80. The index's decline marked the largest one-day drop this year in a trading session dominated by sell orders following a sharp fall at the start of today's session. Volume traded on the first section today was estimated at 950 million shares, compared with Friday's 1.18 billion shares. `` Share prices were lower across the board,'' said <PERSON> Manji </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Nomura </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s largest brokerage. He attributed the index's plunge to a 50-point decline in the Dow Jones Industrial Average in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Friday and the trend toward a weaker yen. In <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Dow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> index fell sharply following a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government report Friday that the nation's producer price index of finished goods rose a full percentage point in February, triggering concern that inflation will grow and interest rates will rise. Instability on the foreign exchange market and higher interest rates tend to discourage market participants from investing in stock, while higher <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates would make the dollar more attractive to foreign currency investors. `` The majority of Japanese investors collected profits by selling off risky issues after they were discouraged by the decline on the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> market and the yen's weakness,'' <PERSON> Ueda </PERSON> said. `` A national holiday -LRB- Tuesday -RRB- also prompted them to sell off,'' he said. Financial markets will be closed in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> on Tuesday, a national holiday marking the spring equinox. In currency dealings, the dollar gained ground and finished trading at 131.92 yen, up 0.85 yen from Friday's 131.07-yen close. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency opened at 131.88 yen and fluctuated in a range between 131.79 yen and 132.08 yen. The 1 percent rise in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer price index of finished goods in February triggered a new wave of worries about inflation and interest rate hikes, said a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, speaking on condition of anonymity. The dollar fluctuated in a fairly tight range in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> mainly because of position adjustments, the trader said. `` Speculative investors sold the dollar for profit-taking around the 132-yen level, while they bought it near 131.70 yen,'' he said. `` The <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> market's dollar-buying interest is still strong, and investors are now concerned about the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> consumer price index in February, due out Tuesday,'' the trader said. He said a higher consumer price index would further encourage investors to buy the dollar and boost its value against the yen.
