<HEAD>Injunction Sought By Shamrock is Granted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES with injunction granted, edits thruout; no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> judge this morning granted an injunction sought by <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Holdings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to keep <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> from completing its share repurchase program, one of the key elements in the instant camera company's fight against a <ORGANIZATION> Shamrock </ORGANIZATION> takeover. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> had said earlier today that if the injunction was not granted, it would tender its 4.9 million Polaroid shares. Vice Chancellor <PERSON> Carolyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Berger </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> granted the injunction for one week while <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> appeals her rulings of last week to the <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. She said the week would give the higher court time to decide if it would accept the appeal. <PERSON> Berger </PERSON> ruled Friday that <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> can go ahead with its plan to buy back 22 percent of its shares and reaffirmed the company's controversial employee stock ownership plan The buyback offer was set to expire at midnight tonight. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> claims the stock buyback plan would stack the deck in favor of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> management in a proxy fight. <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> has been resisting <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>'s hostile takeover bid since July, when the <LOCATION> Burbank </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, company made an unsolicited offer of $ 40 a share. In January, <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON> increased the bid to $ 45. Last July, <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> put 9.7 million shares into an employee stock ownership plan. In January, the company announced a recapitalization plan that included selling $ 300 million of stock to <ORGANIZATION> Corporate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Partners </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> L.P. </ORGANIZATION>, a private investment group. <PERSON> Shamrock </PERSON>, a radio and television concern owned by the <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> family, owns about 4.8 million shares of <ORGANIZATION> Polaroid </ORGANIZATION> and is waging a proxy fight for control of the board of directors at the May 9 annual meeting.
