<HEAD>Supreme Court Clears Partial Merger Of Detroit Papers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Monday cleared the way for the partial merger of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two daily newspapers under a 1970 law that permits an antitrust exemption for financially failing newspapers. The court, over two dissenting votes, set aside an earlier postponement granted by Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. In other decisions, the high court again refused to let states and state agencies be sued for allegedly violating federal copyright laws, and rejected an appeal by workers at a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> nuclear power plant who are challenging their employer's random drug tests. In the <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> newspapers case, a federal appeals court panel in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> voted 2-1 on Jan. 27 to uphold then-Attorney General <PERSON> Edwin </PERSON> <PERSON> Meese </PERSON>'s decision to allow the newspapers to form a joint operating agreement under the federal Newspaper Preservation Act. Under the joint operating agreement, the <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> and The Detroit News would combine their business, advertising and production departments but maintain separate news and editorial staffs. A group of <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> readers and advertisers who sued to stop the partial merger contend that the <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, a morning newspaper owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is not a failing newspaper even though it lost $ 10 milion a year between 1981 and 1986. The opponents, calling themselves <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, say the Free Press and News, which lost $ 50 million in the same period, were unprofitable solely because both papers cut prices in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out of business. <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, which owns the News, is the nation's largest newspaper publishing group. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> is the second largest. In the copyright case, the justices refused to revive allegations that <ORGANIZATION> UCLA </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> state-run university, illegally copied a company's computer programs and instruction manuals. Nine major motion picture studios had urged the court to hear BV Engineering's appeal to broaden protection against what they said is widespread copyright infringement. The movie producers said, for example, that prisons in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Rhode </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> are refusing to pay for films shown to inmates. The justices on Feb. 21 had turned away a similar appeal by a photographer who accused a state university in <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> of unauthorized use of his photographs. In the drug-testing case, the court, without comment, left intact a ruling that threw out, at least temporarily, a lawsuit attacking the tests. The justices already are studying the validity of drug tests in three other cases, one involving a private employer and two concerning federal workers or federal regulations. The case acted on Monday stems from tests initiated by <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Edison </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> at its <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Onofre </LOCATION> nuclear plant. In other business-related decisions: _ The court turned away a still-pending, big-money antitrust dispute over the sale of raw milk The justices, without comment, let stand a federal appeals court ruling that could cost millions for two cooperative associations of dairy farmers and a marketing agent for dairy cooperatives. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in 1982 ruled against <ORGANIZATION> Mid-America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dairymen </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Springfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, and the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Milk </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperative </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. _ The court refused to let <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> officials tax the income of railway workers who live elsewhere but pass through the state as crew members on nonstop freight trains It let stand a ruling that such a tax on crews of <ORGANIZATION> Burlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Railroad </ORGANIZATION> would violate the Constitution and be unfair to the workers. _ The court refused to hear an appeal by a federal judge in <LOCATION> Pittsburgh </LOCATION> who issued orders in the bankruptcy case of <ORGANIZATION> Jeannette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> glass company after he disqualified himself from presiding over the matter The court, without comment, left intact a ruling that set aside the orders by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON>.
