<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Stocks declined on the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Monday, reflecting what brokers called persistent worries about further rises in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates. The market remained preoccupied with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inflation outlook following news Friday that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producer price index rose 1 percent in February, dealers said. Analysts were anxiously awaiting the Tuesday release of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> February consumer price index to see whether it confirms inflationary worries and maybe triggers another increase in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> interest rates. The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed 19.5 points, or 0.9 percent, lower at 2,053.6. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 30-share index closed 14.6 points lower at 1,690.9. <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> 500-share index fell 11.64 points to close at 1,170.68. Volume totaled 384.6 million shares, well down from 535.2 million shares on Friday.
