<HEAD>Wheat Falls Sharply As Snowstorm Slams Kansas</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS corn price to rising, sted falling, in last graf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Wheat futures prices closed sharply lower Monday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> amid reports of a blizzard in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> but other grain and soybean futures advanced, with soybeans posting fairly strong gains. The wheat market had opened lower and remained depressed throughout the morning on perceptions that weekend precipitation in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> had improved growing conditions for the maturing winter wheat crop and added badly needed moisture to the soil. Wheat doubled its losses in the afternoon as selling increased following reports that wind-driven snow had closed several highways, including Interstate 70, in western <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, an area especially in need of moisture. `` The market went through some liquidation, despite the fact that when we look at all the precipitation recording during the past 24 hours, it wo n't necessarily be characterized as a drought-breaker,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, a grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Soybean futures contined their recent upward trend on continuing concerns about tight supplies of soybeans for immediate delivery. At the close, wheat was 5 -RCB- cents to 8 -LCB- cents lower with the contract for delivery in March at $ 4.27 a bushel; corn was -RCB- cent to 1 -RCB- cents higher with March at $ 2.79 a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent lower to 1 cent higher with March at $ 2.09 a bushel; soybeans were 3 cents to 8 cents higher with March at $ 7.77 a bushel.
