<FIRST>u f AM-FraudIndictment     03-20 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fraud Indictment,0669</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Haas Securities Chairman Indicted on Fraud Charges</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The former head of a defunct Wall Street brokerage firm was charged Monday with illegally inflating the prices of three stocks in a two-year scheme undone by the 1987 stock market crash. In a 15-count indictment handed up by a federal grand jury, <PERSON> Eugene </PERSON> <PERSON> Laff </PERSON>, former chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Haas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, was charged in what authorities called the first securities fraud case emanating from the Oct. 19, 1987, crash. The indictment is the latest in a three-year federal crackdown on Wall Street crime and the first by the <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney's office since the government formed nationwide securities and commodities task forces in January Laff, 51, of <LOCATION> Greenwich </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, was charged with conspiring to manipulate the prices of three over-the-counter stocks to increase the value of substantial holdings owned by <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Haas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>. The indictment is based on the confessions of <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Aslanian </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 29, a former <PERSON> Haas </PERSON> trader and presidentwho pleaded guilty in January to conspiracy and agreed to cooperate with the government. He has not been sentenced. `` I think it's a reflection of an ongoing problem of penny stock fraud,'' Acting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> said. `` It's one that deserves our serious consideration generally.'' Attorneys for <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> denied the charges, suggesting that co-conspirators, including <PERSON> Aslanian </PERSON>, wrongly accused <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> of participating in the alleged fraud. `` It seems that in looking at the indictment a lot of conduct of other individuals appears to be attributed to Mr. <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> based on the theories of conspiracy,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lang </PERSON>, an attorney for Laff. The indictment alleges that <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> took part in a conspiracy starting in January 1986 to manipulate the stock prices of <ORGANIZATION> Flores </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, T.S. <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> O </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tires </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. He is charged with conspiracy, securities fraud, mail fraud and obstructing a <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> investigation. Each of the 15 counts carries a maximum five years in jail and $ 250,000 fine. <ORGANIZATION> Haas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, through Laff, allegedly cornered the market on shares of the stocks and set artificially high prices. By sustaining the high price, <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> allegedly was able to reap a large profit. The indictment does not specify how much money was involved in the schemes. <ORGANIZATION> Haas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, a 75-year-old firm that had 12,000 customers before going out of business nine days after the crash, is now liquidating its assets in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> proceedings. The indictment says <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> acted as a `` market maker'' on the stocks by being ready to buy and sell a specific stock at prices published by the firm. Laff, <PERSON> Aslanian </PERSON> and several unnamed co-conspirators, the indictment says, allegedly raised the prices of the manipulated stocks and placed large blocks of shares in friendly accounts that were concealed from the public to create the appearance of demand. The indictment names, but does not charge, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorin </PERSON>, president of a private investment company that allegedly controlled the accounts and bought blocks of the three stocks. <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> made `` bogus, non-market, unauthorized'' transactions that artificially boosted the share prices without money ever changing hands, the indictment claims. Laff then sold some stocks accumulated by <ORGANIZATION> Haas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> at the inflated prices. The charge also says <PERSON> Laff </PERSON> published false information about the stocks, made unauthorized sales to customers who did not have the money to pay and refused to accept sell orders from customers. <ORGANIZATION> Haas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> went belly-up after the crash because it no longer had the capital to stay in business. Authorities said the alleged scheme to manipulate the stocks could n't be maintained after the market drop and the share prices collapsed. After the crash, investors demanded information about the stocks. <ORGANIZATION> Haas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> allegedly was able to sustain the prices for several days after the crash until it filed for bankruptcy and the manipulated share prices plunged.
</TEXT>
