<HEAD>Sales to Japan Top Europe for First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> will sell more than $ 8.2 billion in farm products to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> this year, topping sales to western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> for the first time, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> official said Monday. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> are expected to drop to $ 7.3 billion for the year ending Sept. 30, <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee on rural development. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales to all of western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> are expected to reach only $ 7.8 billion, he said. In the year ended last Sept. 30, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> reached $ 7.5 billion, compared to $ 7.3 billion to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The biggest gains for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm sales are coming from the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> countries, <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said. He said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is now the biggest importer of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat and predicted big increases in exports to <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` We are transferring our resources to that area _ that's where the future lies,'' <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sims </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Argiculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> general sales manager, said 1989 will be the last year in which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> will get <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government-supported loans to encourage purchases. <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> said total <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm exports this year are projected to rise to $ 38 billion, up $ 2.7 billion from 1988. He attributed the increase to higher prices caused by last summer's drought, which is expected to reduce the volume of farm exports by 2 percent.
</TEXT>
