<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0373</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crude Prices Plummet; Products Decline Moderately</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Crude oil prices plummeted in heavy trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Monday, reversing last week's rally in which prices rose nearly $ 2 a barrel. The April contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, dropped 82 cents to a closing price of $ 19.51 a barrel, taking back 45 percent of the previous week's gains. On Friday, the April contract closed at $ 20.33, the highest level since Aug. 14, 1987, when crude prices were $ 20.57 a barrel. It capped a week-long rally during which prices rose $ 1.83 a barrel from the previous Friday. Refined oil products traded on the exchange also declined, but not as sharply. Unleaded gasoline for April delivery declined .14 cent to 55.48 cents a gallon, while April heating oil lost .21 cent to settle at 53.36 cents a gallon. Traders said the crude market was technically driven, fueled in part by normal dealings on the last day of the April contract. Other contract months for 1989 had only modest declines. But market fundamentals had not warranted the high price levels reached on Friday, they said. `` The market realized that and took profits today,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Steel </PERSON>, an energy broker at <ORGANIZATION> Refco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. The market had expected problems with April deliveries to underpin the recent price rise but they never materialized, some analysts said. `` Instead, the market got a bucket of cold water in the form of the April squeeze not developing,'' said <PERSON> Nauman </PERSON> <PERSON> Barakat </PERSON>, vice president of energy investments at <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Steel </PERSON> said once prices broke through the $ 20 mark on the downside, the momentum picked up `` That prompted a sharp sell-off,'' he said. Strong demand and declining world oil production have helped boost prices recently, but energy specialists had forecast that the market could not sustain prices much higher. `` Demand is not that strong. Given that and given expected slowdowns in economic growth it does n't justify oil being over $ 20 a barrel,'' <PERSON> Steel </PERSON> said. Brokers said the slower decline in product prices helped an even sharper fall in crude prices.
</TEXT>
