<SECOND>AM-Detroit Newspapers,0615</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Ends Detroit JOA Delay; Opponents Plan Further Appeal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With AM-Scotus-Business, Bjt ^By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents of the partial merger of <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>'s two major daily newspapers will ask the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to hear their appeal, despite the court's refusal Monday to further delay the business deal The court, with only two justices dissenting, lifted without comment a postponement granted March 4 by Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>. The order cleared the way for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, owned by <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, to merge their business and production operations under an antitrust exemption allowed by the 1970 Newspaper Preservation Act. The <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s approval of the partial merger was challenged by a coalition of newspaper readers and advertisers, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Citizens for an <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, and Public Citizen, a Washington-based advocacy group. `` We lost a battle in the war,'' said <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON>, attorney for Public Citizen. `` On the other hand, I feel much better because there were two dissents than if there would have been no dissents at all. The fact that we got two dissents puts us in the serious category.'' With the lifting of the stay, the newspapers can begin immediately to put their partial merger into effect. But a <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> vice president, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said it was too early to discuss timing of the merger. `` Obviously there have to be some discussions with our friends at <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON> said. Opponents' intention to continue their appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> means the newspapers had to decide whether to proceed with the merger at the risk of the court later ordering it dismantled. `` Once the merger is implemented, the egg has been scrambled, and how do you unscramble the egg,'' said <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Spaeth </PERSON>, a political scientist at <ORGANIZATION> Michigan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lansing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, who specializes in the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. `` If the merger was consummated and then terminated, it would be almost like starting up a new newspaper, and you just do n't do that in a metropolitan area on a daily basis at this point in time,'' he said. <PERSON> Schultz </PERSON> said he was confident there were sufficient votes on the court to grant a petition to hear the cases. The court's order did not specify how many of the seven non-dissenting justices in fact supported lifting the stay. <PERSON> Spaeth </PERSON>, however, said the court's refusal to delay the merger made it unlikely they would consent to hear the case. Justices <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> voted to extend the postponement until the court considers a formal appeal by those who oppose the partial merger. `` I ca n't think of a nicer way to start out the week,'' Free Press Publisher <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> said. `` Finally, we seem to be near the point where we can assure the readers of the Free Press that their newspaper is saved.'' Neither <ORGANIZATION> Gannett </ORGANIZATION> nor the News commented on the justice's decision. Opponents of the joint operating agreement argued that the Free Press was not a failing newspaper even though it lost $ 10 million a year between 1981 and 1986. The News lost $ 50 million in the same period. The losses were due solely to price-cutting by the newspapers in an unsuccessful effort to force each other out of business, the opponents said. The opponents' emergency request to the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said the agreement `` threatens the independence of daily newspapers in 25 cities'' where, like <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION>, competing newspapers still exist. <ORGANIZATION> Knight-Ridder </ORGANIZATION> has threatened to close the Free Press if the joint operating agreement is denied.
