<HEAD>Wheat Futures Tumble As Rain, Snow Moisten Fields</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Wheat futures prices fell sharply Monday on reports that badly needed precipitation in the <LOCATION> Great </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plains </LOCATION> had improved growing conditions for the winter wheat crop. Other grain and soybean futures advanced, with soybeans posting some fairly strong gains. On other markets, precious metals were mixed; copper futures fell; livestock and meat futures were mostly higher; and energy futures finished mostly lower. Wheat settled 5 -RCB- cents to 8 \ cents lower on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> with the contract for delivery in March at $ 4.26 \ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 2 cents higher with March at $ 2.79 \ a bushel; oats were -LCB- cent lower to 1 cent higher with March at $ 2.09 a bushel; soybeans were 2 -RCB- cents to 8 -LCB- cents higher with March at $ 7.76 -RCB- The wheat market had opened lower and remained depressed throughout the morning after the weekend precipitation in the Plains. Winter wheat now is maturing in the central and southern states and northern farmers are preparing for spring planting. Selling increased in the afternoon, doubling wheat's losses, following reports that wind-driven snow had closed several highways, including Interstate 70, in western <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, an area especially in need of moisture. `` The market went through some liquidation, despite the fact that when we look at all the precipitation recording during the past 24 hours, it wo n't necessarily be characterized as a drought-breaker,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>, a grain specialist with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Analyst <PERSON> Katharina </PERSON> <PERSON> Zimmer </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Merr