<BYLINE>By RONALD POWERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> lowered his offer for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>' shuttle by at least $ 125 million Monday because of damage to the service by a walkout by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> and pilots. `` I bought something that had a 57 percent share of the market,'' the billionaire said in a telephone interview. `` That share has deteriorated considerably.'' In response, Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> sent <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> a letter Monday afternoon informing him the carrier is seeking other bids for the shuttle. The letter says <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> has recently received `` other offers unsolicited'' and invites <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> to re-submit a bid. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> announced last October that he planned to acquire the lucrative three-city shuttle service from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s parent <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for $ 365 million. But on Monday, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said he wants to cut the offered price by more than a third. `` I'm looking for a reduction in excess of $ 125 million,'' he said, adding that he considered $ 200 million a reasonable offer. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, an airline analyst for the investment firm <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stanley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>'s move could reopen the bidding for the shuttle while signaling the developer's reluctance to get into the airline business. Art Kent, a spokesman for Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, did not return repeated calls for comment. Excerpts from <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s letter to <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, signed by <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON>, senior vice president for legal affairs at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, were released in a statement. `` We believe it is our obligation to all our constituencies _ creditors, shareholders, employees and the communities and traveling public we service _ to ensure that any shuttle sale is completed on the best possible terms for <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> wrote to <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. `` Your intention to not proceed at this time on the terms in the Oct. 12 agreement requires that we take action, consistent with our obligations under the reorganization process to solicit offers from third parties for the shuttle.'' On March 4, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s 8,500-member <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union, chiefly mechanics and baggage handlers, walked off the job. The refusal of most of the airline's pilots to cross the Machinists' picket lines has forced Eastern to file for protection from creditors under the bankruptcy laws. Eastern's hourly shuttle service, usually a profitable operation linking <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, has been flying during the strike. In the first days of the walkout, most Eastern shuttle flights flew nearly empty, but the airline has been trying to rebuild its business with a number of passenger incentives, including promotional fares as low as $ 12. Fares returned to normal on Saturday. Eastern made another pitch Monday to lure shuttle passengers. Starting March 23, when the cut-rate weekday fares of $ 49 return to $ 99, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> will offer an on-time guarantee on shuttle flights. If the shuttle plane is more than five minutes pulling away from the gate, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> will greet the arriving passengers with refunds on the spot or free tickets for other shuttle flights. The exceptions would be delays caused by airport problems or severe weather. A rival shuttle service operated by New York-based <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been flying with full passenger loads. <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> has seen business on its shuttle service double since the strike began, said <ORGANIZATION> Pan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Am </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Manners </PERSON>. The airline has added flights and introduced larger aircraft to accommodate the increased demand, she said. In a letter sent Monday to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>, <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said, `` Last fall I agreed to buy a fully operational shuttle which held nearly 60 percent of the market, commanded the principal loyalty and confidence of business travelers and provided excellent service to the customer. `` However, as you and I discussed, the shuttle has become an entirely different business in that its market share and customer base may be lost for some time to come, if not forever.'' The shuttle `` is worth considerably less than the price negotiated last fall,'' <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> said. Eastern spokesman <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Ashlock </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> said the airline has been encouraged by shuttle traffic and it was showing signs of luring back its regular business travelers. He referred requests for comment about the <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> letter to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON>'s <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> office also referred calls to the <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION> headquarters. <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Nobles </PERSON>, president of the Trump Shuttle, the company formed in anticipation of purchasing the Eastern shuttle, estimated <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> was now carrying about 20 percent of the shuttle market. Systemwide, Eastern is operating only about 100 flights a day, about one-tenth of its normal flight schedule. The airline has begun advertising for new pilots, while acknowledging there are no near-term prospects for expanding its operations. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>, who promised to rename the hourly service `` The Trump Shuttle'' and redecorate the blue-silver <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 727s, said Monday he was still interested in buying the operation and was prepared to close a deal with <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> within a week. `` I'm not surprised he'd want to lower his price considering the strike and the troubles -LRB- Eastern's -RRB- had,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Decker </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Duff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Phelps </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>.
