<HEAD>Convenience Store Owner Says Losses Reflect Buyout</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Southland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, owner of 7-Eleven convenience stores, Monday reported it lost $ 37 millionin the fourth quarter and $ 216.2 million for all of last year, reflecting high interest costs and other expenses related to its 1987 leveraged buyout. The losses occurred despite strong operating results for its 7-Eleven stores. Revenue amounted to $ 1.97 billion in the three months ended Dec. 31 and $ 7.99 billion in all of 1988. Because of the buyout, the seven months ended July 31, 1987 were reported on a separate accounting basis than subsequent periods, which means results from the two periods within 1987 can not be added together to produce 1987 full-year financial results, and no full-year comparisons can be made between 1987 and 1988. <ORGANIZATION> Southland </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation and amortization was $ 494.3 million, including $ 16.5 million from divested operations, the company said. <PERSON> Jere </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Southland </ORGANIZATION>'s president and chief executive officer, called that figure `` the most appropriate measure of our progress.'' `` We're very pleased overall with the company's operating and financial achievements during its first full year after undergoing one of the largest leveraged buyouts in history,'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said in a prepared statement. <ORGANIZATION> Southland </ORGANIZATION> added 600 convenience stores to its 7-Eleven international operation in 1988. The division now includes nearly 5,300 stores operated by licensees and affiliates in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and 19 foreign countries. <ORGANIZATION> Southland </ORGANIZATION> operates about 7,000 additional convenience stores in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, and owns a 50 percent interest in <ORG