<HEAD>Hamburger Chain Founder Loses Bid to Dismiss Insider Trading Charge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The founder of the <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s Jr. hamburger chain lost a bid Monday to have a federal insider trading case against him and several relatives dismissed. In rejecting a dismissal motion by <PERSON> Carl </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>'s attorney, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafeedie </PERSON> ruled that a jury should hear <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON>'s claim that the civil case against him is based only on circumstantial evidence. <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> is accused of passing on information that allowed several relatives to avoid losses on stock in <ORGANIZATION> Carl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Karcher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, which runs 460 <PERSON> Carl </PERSON>'s Jr. fast-food outlets in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> and the West. The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> case, filed in April 1988, alleges that various <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> relatives and one company executive sold stock to avoid losses totaling $ 310,000 in advance of an unfavorable earnings report in 1984. The civil suit seeks treble damages. <PERSON> Karcher </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON>, are accused of passing insider information to relatives, but are n't accused of selling stock themselves. Other defendants include the couple's son, <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON>; daughters, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher-Garrett </PERSON>, <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> LeVecke </PERSON>, <PERSON> Catherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Karcher-Everly </PERSON> and her husband, <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON>; and son-in-law, <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Fergus </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> DeShano </PERSON>, who was accounting dire